export const leadEssays: Record<string, LeadEssay> = {
  "01-reality-of-ownership": {
    slug: "01-reality-of-ownership",
    title: "The reality of ownership",
    standfirst:
      "What the first three years of yacht ownership actually look like, in time and in money. The folkloric numbers do not survive contact with the data.",
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "In 2025 the global market for yachts above 24 metres turned over USD 8.5 billion in transactions, a 70 percent rise on the year before, eclipsed in the past decade only by the post-Covid surge of 2021. Stewart Campbell, Managing Director of BOAT International, identifies the largest single driver of the 2025 surge as the 100 percent depreciation provision in the United States' One Big Beautiful Bill Act. The market grew because the tax code changed, not because the demand structure shifted. This is the first thing a first-time owner should know. The headline numbers are noisier than the underlying reality.",
      "The First Owner’s Reference exists to tell that underlying reality with a frame the trade press is structurally unable to apply. Trade press is funded by the yards, brokers, and management companies whose interests sit on the other side of certain conversations. The First Owner’s Reference is funded differently and is able, by structure rather than by argument, to have those conversations. This chapter opens with the question every first-time buyer asks within the first eighteen months of owning a yacht: what does this actually cost.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The folklore of the 10 percent rule" },
      "The industry shorthand for annual operating cost is 10 percent of the yacht's purchase price per year. Brokers quote it. Management companies quote it. Wealth managers, when they engage with the topic at all, quote it. The rule has no traceable origin. No primary source attributes it to a single study or institution. It survives because it is roughly correct for new, mid-sized, lightly used yachts and because it is easy.",
      "It is also wrong for most readers of The First Owner’s Reference.",
      "YachtBuyer, in published analysis, calls the rule \"at best, obsolete or even misleading\" for older or larger crewed vessels. The arithmetic is simple. As the asset depreciates, the percentage rises mechanically, since running cost is a function of size and complexity, not residual value. A 50m yacht that cost EUR 50 million new and is worth EUR 30 million eight years later does not become 40 percent cheaper to operate. Its operating cost may have risen with crew inflation, insurance hardening, and refit accumulation. The same EUR 5 million annual run rate that was 10 percent of value at purchase is now nearly 17 percent.",
      "Working ranges from independent practitioner sources (Foreland Marine, Fraser Yachts, Ocean Independence, Luxcenture) cluster between 8 and 15 percent for the first decade. For yachts over 40 metres, or older than seven years, the empirical band is closer to 12 to 20 percent. Charter-active vessels run higher still.",
      "The honest position: budget on 12 to 15 percent for a typical 40m to 50m new build operated privately at moderate use, and revise upward for charter operation, larger size, or older age. Do not let any party who is paid contingent on a deal closing tell you otherwise.",
      { type: "h2", text: "What you actually buy" },
      "The cost categories compound in an unintuitive way. The crew, not the fuel, is the dominant line. On a typical 50m yacht the breakdown looks roughly as follows.",
      "Crew accounts for 30 to 40 percent of annual operating cost, and rises with size. A captain on a 50m yacht costs EUR 10,000 to 16,000 per month, per the YPI Crew 2026 salary guide. A captain on an 80m runs EUR 16,000 to 23,000. Quay Crew's 2025 captain survey records a 7 percent year on year increase in the 70 to 79m bracket and confirms 63 percent of captains are now on time-for-time rotation. Senior crew are the new bottleneck of the industry; their pay continues to rise where junior crew has plateaued.",
      "Maintenance and repair, 14 to 18 percent. Insurance, 10 to 14 percent. Berths and marina fees, 8 to 12 percent. Fuel, 8 to 12 percent, higher on charter-active hulls. Management fees, 3 to 5 percent. Regulatory and class compliance, 2 to 3 percent. Contingency, 6 to 10 percent. The remainder is provisioning, communications, owner travel, and the various lines that simply happen.",
      "A 40m motor yacht at moderate use (400 cruising hours per year, Mediterranean diesel at EUR 1.30 to 1.80 per litre) runs EUR 130,000 to 250,000 per year on fuel alone. A 50m displacement yacht at the same use level runs to EUR 250,000 plus. None of this is exceptional. It is the cost of operating any large machine in salt water with people aboard.",
      "What 4 to 8 weeks of annual use a year actually buys, then, is a fixed cost structure that runs whether the yacht is being used or not. Ocean Independence's owner-usage data places typical use at 4 to 8 weeks. Committed users reach 12 to 16 weeks. Above that, charter operation is the only economically rational frame, and even that does not solve the problem.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The folklore of the 10 percent rule survives because it is roughly correct for new, mid-sized, lightly used yachts. It is wrong for most readers of The First Owner’s Reference.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "The depreciation reality" },
      "The standard depreciation curve, drawn from broker-aggregated data at Yatco, IYC, and Yacht Hunter, runs roughly as follows. Year one: 10 to 20 percent decline from purchase price. Years two to five: a further 6 to 8 percent annually, compounding. By year five, a typical hull has lost 40 to 50 percent of its original value. The curve flattens after year five.",
      "Quality builders hold value materially better. Feadship, Lurssen, Royal Huisman, Vitters, and Baltic Yachts hulls can lose only single-digit percentages annually after year five. The pedigree premium is real, although the up-front cost is also higher. There is no peer-reviewed academic study of yacht depreciation; all published curves are broker-aggregated and self-reported, which is itself a finding.",
      "What this means for a first-time owner is straightforward. The yacht is not an investment. It is a depreciating asset whose depreciation is roughly the same magnitude as the annual operating cost in the early years. A USD 30 million yacht held for five years and operated at moderate use will typically have lost in the order of USD 12 to 15 million in value and consumed another USD 15 to 22 million in opex. A nine-figure hold cost over the period is the realistic frame. Numbers presented without that frame tend to be a broker headline rather than a working budget.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The charter delusion" },
      "The single most consistent piece of broker advice given to first-time owners is that charter operation can offset ownership cost. For the median yacht in the median programme, the arithmetic does not bear that out.",
      "BOAT International's published case studies are the cleanest public evidence. A 48m motor yacht at EUR 250,000 to 310,000 per week, 7 charter weeks per year, generated EUR 1,592,000 in net charter income against EUR 1,575,000 in running cost. Effectively break-even, after the owner's own usage costs are accounted for separately. A 47m sailing yacht at EUR 110,000 to 125,000 per week, 9 weeks: EUR 444,000 loss. An 85m motor yacht at EUR 850,000 to 950,000 per week, 8 weeks: EUR 430,000 loss. The successful exception is the owner-optimised 60m at 12 weeks generating up to EUR 2 million net positive, which depends on disciplined operation, premium charter rates, and an owner willing to give up the prime weeks of the season.",
      "Most charter operations subsidise rather than recover ownership cost. The growth in the global yacht charter market (Precedence Research records USD 8.39 billion in 2024 forecast to reach approximately USD 16.92 billion by 2033, a compound annual growth of around 8.1 percent; Mordor Intelligence and IMARC Group publish similar trajectories) is driven by charter demand, not by owners profiting from charter. The two are different markets with different economics.",
      "The honest framing to take into the first conversation with any broker proposing a charter-funded acquisition: charter does not pay for ownership for the median operator. It can pay for ownership for a small minority of disciplined programmes. The first yacht is rarely the one for which the conditions of that minority are already in place.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The ownership case, honestly stated" },
      "None of this argues against ownership. It argues against ownership undertaken on the assumption that the cost is what the broker said it was. The right ownership decision, taken with full visibility of the financial reality, is one of the great purchases a person can make. The same decision, taken on the back of folkloric numbers and contingent advice, tends to be among the more costly errors a UHNW buyer can make.",
      "Ownership makes sense when the owner intends to use the yacht for at least 12 weeks per year, plans to hold for at least seven years, has the cash flow to absorb operating cost without strain, and wants the kind of programme that a charter cannot deliver. Repeated, predictable, family-led use of a known asset that has been specified, crewed, and operated to the owner's preferences. That is the genuine ownership case. It is not financial. It is operational.",
      "The first task is to ask whether your intended use pattern fits this case. The running cost calculator on this site lets you run your own numbers through a structure calibrated against MYBA, Pantaenius, Quay Crew, IGY, and aggregated industry practitioner data. Source assumptions are named on every category. The answer should be sobering.",
      "If after that exercise the answer is still ownership, the rest of The First Owner’s Reference is written with that reader in mind. The remaining chapters cover how the market is structured, how the industry actually works, what the acquisition process looks like, the new build versus brokerage decision, refit, operations, and how to build the team that protects the buyer through all of it. Read in any order. Apply the independence test in chapter 9 to anyone proposing to advise.",
    ],
  },

  "02-reading-the-market": {
    slug: "02-reading-the-market",
    title: "Reading the market in 2026",
    standfirst:
      "More wealth has been created in fewer hands than at any point in recorded economic history. The order book contracted for the second consecutive year. The market is becoming harder to buy correctly, not easier.",
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "Two facts about the market in 2026 are essential and rarely stated together. The first is that more wealth has been created in fewer hands than at any point in recorded economic history. The second is that the order book for yachts above 24 metres contracted for the second consecutive year. The number of new buyers is rising sharply. The number of yachts available to be bought is shrinking.",
      "This chapter reads the market in those terms. The trade press often characterises the moment as a boom. By a more careful reading, it is a structural narrowing of supply against an expanding pool of demand, which produces price discipline at the top, scarcity at the established yards, and a bifurcation between well-priced inventory that moves and over-priced inventory that rots. The market is becoming harder to buy correctly, not easier.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The wealth side" },
      "The Knight Frank Wealth Sizing Model, in its 20th edition for 2026, places the global UHNWI population (those with net wealth above USD 30 million) at 713,626. In 2021 the figure was 551,435. The five-year change is 162,191 new UHNWIs, equivalent to 89 individuals crossing the USD 30 million threshold every single day for five years.",
      "Of those new UHNWIs, 41 percent were created in the United States. The Knight Frank forecast for 2031 has the United States accounting for 41 percent of the world's UHNW population, up from 33 percent in 2021 and 35 percent in 2026. The concentration is intensifying. India, by contrast, was 2 percent of the global UHNW total five years ago and is forecast to reach a UHNWI population of 25,217 by 2031, up from 19,877 today, the fastest absolute growth of any economy. Saudi Arabia leads billionaire growth at 183 percent forecast over five years. Indonesia leads UHNWI growth at 82 percent.",
      "The Capgemini World Wealth Report 2025 adds the second consequential frame: USD 83.5 trillion of wealth will be inherited by Gen X, millennials, and Gen Z by 2048. Within that transfer, women receive a significant share by 2035. And, crucially, 81 percent of next-generation HNWIs intend to switch from their parents' wealth management firm within one to two years of inheritance. The reader of The First Owner’s Reference is therefore likely to be one of two profiles: a newly liquidated principal, or an heir whose first action is to fire the adviser their parents used.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The yacht side" },
      "Against that demand picture, the supply side is contracting in unit count. The 2026 BOAT International Global Order Book records 1,093 yachts of 24m and above on order or in build, down from 1,138 in the 2025 edition. This is the second consecutive annual decline by unit count. The headline that recurs in trade press, that the market is at a peak, is true only by length and tonnage. Average length on the order book has risen to 40.8m and 551 GT, the highest ever recorded, but the unit count peaked in the 2023 to 2024 window and has eased.",
      "Italy is now the dominant production geography. 568 units, 52 percent of the global order book by units. Azimut Benetti Group is ranked first for the 26th consecutive year, with 5,924 metres of length under construction across 163 yachts, 23 percent of global market by length. Sanlorenzo with Nautor Swan sits second at 4,698 metres across 130 yachts. The Netherlands is second by tonnage at 107,796 GT across 66 units, reflecting the larger average length of Dutch builds. Turkey is third at 82,383 GT across 141 units. Germany is fourth at 78,651 GT across 18 units, the smallest unit count among the four leading countries because German output is concentrated at the very top.",
      "Top-tier yards are sold out. Lurssen books extend through mid-2027 at minimum; the yard acquired the insolvent Nobiskrug in 2024 and 2025, securing additional large-build capacity. Feadship slot availability is openly discussed in trade press as extending to 2028 to 2029, with Project Solent confirmed for 2027. Oceanco delivered the 111m DreAMBoat in 18 months in November 2025, the counter-example of speed at the top. Heesen has run a speculative-build model since 2023 with full backlog through 2025 and beyond.",
      "What this means for a first-time buyer entering in 2026: the major decision is not which yard to commission, but whether to take a brokerage hull now, take a slot at a mid-tier yard with capacity, or wait three to four years for a delivery slot at a top-tier German or Dutch builder. Each path has different cost, risk, and time profiles. They are not interchangeable.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The number of new buyers is rising sharply. The number of yachts available to be bought is shrinking.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "Brokerage in 2025" },
      "The brokerage market in 2025 was, by value, the strongest year on record. BOAT International reports total brokerage transactions of around EUR 7.5 billion across the over-30 metre segment. Edmiston\u2019s own 2025 market review records its house transactions in excess of EUR 2.6 billion, with the firm reporting more 40 metre and above yachts sold than any other brokerage and more EUR 20 million plus yachts than any competitor. Yachts asking over EUR 40 million accounted for 7 percent of sales by volume but 52 percent of total value across the segment. Denison Yachting\u2019s broader count, which includes 79 ft and above, came in at 470 yachts.",
      "The wide divergence between the segment 30 m+ count and the Denison broader count of 470 is editorially important. Both numbers appear in trade press, often side by side, treated as comparable. They are not. The 30 m+ figure is the one that matters for the readership of The First Owner’s Reference. The broader figure inflates the apparent size of the market and obscures the genuine scarcity in the segment that first-time UHNW buyers consider.",
      "The pricing discipline is the defining feature of 2025. Denison reports a median days-on-market of 277, the lowest in their five-year series. Listings that did not sell sat 573 days on average. Average price reductions per listing fell from 1.36 in Q1 2024 to 0.76 in Q1 2025. Average reduction rate improved from minus 12.6 percent to minus 8.97 percent. The market is bifurcating into well-priced movers and shelf-stayers. The implication is that buyers entering in 2026 should expect serious inventory to move quickly, not patiently.",
      "Asking prices have softened around 7 percent from peak brokerage levels of 2023. The 70 metre and above segment hit record values in 2025, with the 119m Feadship Breakthrough sale in September the largest single transaction. The very top of the market and the value-driven middle are diverging.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The geographic shift" },
      "Three claims about the geographic shift recur in trade press, only one of which the data supports.",
      "The claim that the United States now dominates is supported. BOAT International puts US share of yacht transactions at 45 to 50 percent in 2025, the highest on record, partly driven by the One Big Beautiful Bill Act 100 percent depreciation provision. Denison reports US-built yacht sales at 130 in 2025, up from 103 in 2024.",
      "The claim that European share is collapsing is partly supported. European share of brokerage value fell to 52 percent in 2024 from 60 percent the prior year. The Western Mediterranean transaction count doubled year on year in Q1 2025, from 11 to 27 in the French and Italian Rivieras. So the European share is declining but the European market remains the second largest by a wide margin.",
      "The claim that Asia is in retreat is wrong. The Asia-Pacific operating fleet over 30m grew from 372 in 2022 to 445 in 2023 to 530 in 2024. Approximately 20 percent annual growth. Asia-Pacific national ownership stands at 343. The \"Asian retreat\" framing in trade press is not supported by ownership data; it reflects new-build order patterns rather than fleet growth.",
      "Russia is a similar misframe. SuperYacht Times iQ data shows Russian ownership share moved from 9.1 percent in 2022 to 8.1 percent in 2023. A decline, but not a collapse, despite the post-2022 narrative. Ownership through proxies and structures has largely survived the sanctions environment.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Reading 2026 correctly" },
      "Three implications follow for a first-time buyer reading the market this year.",
      "First, the wealth pool entering the market is overwhelmingly American, increasingly self-made, and includes a growing proportion of next-generation inheritors who are less loyal to incumbent advisers than any prior generation. The supply side has not adjusted to this.",
      "Second, the supply side is concentrated at Italian volume yards (Azimut Benetti, Sanlorenzo) for unit count and at Northern European custom yards (Lurssen, Feadship, Oceanco) for prestige and value retention, with the prestige tier sold out for several years. A first-time buyer in 2026 cannot have a 50m Lurssen by 2027. The decision is between a 2030 Lurssen, a 2027 Heesen, or a brokerage hull available now.",
      "Third, the brokerage market has discipline that did not exist two years ago. Well-priced inventory moves in months. Over-priced inventory rots for a year and a half. The buyer who pays close attention to days-on-market and price-reduction history will find that this is the most legible the brokerage market has been in a decade.",
      "Trade press is structurally less able to set this out with the same clarity. The First Owner’s Reference is not constrained in the same way. Read on the evidence, the market in 2026 is harder to buy correctly than it was two years ago, not easier.",
    ],
  },

  "03-how-the-industry-works": {
    slug: "03-how-the-industry-works",
    title: "How the industry actually works",
    standfirst:
      "The superyacht market is one of the few luxury sectors in which the buyer routinely pays for the seller's adviser. This is the chapter nobody publishes a magazine about.",
    readingTime: "9 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "The first thing a new owner often learns, some months after the first contract is signed, is that the structure of the market places most of the people around the acquisition on the other side of the table. The broker who walked them around shipyards in Viareggio and Vlissingen, who introduced them to the captain candidates, who recommended the law firm and the surveyor and the management company, was paid by the seller. In some transactions, the same broker also represented the seller. The information did not arrive with the introduction; the questions that would have surfaced it are not in the standard first-time buyer\u2019s kit.",
      "This is not bad practice. It is the structure of the market. It has worked this way for half a century. The reason it persists is that the alternative, which is for the buyer to pay their own adviser at the rates such advice actually costs, tends to feel expensive at the moment of the decision and only feels cheap years later, when the reader is on their second yacht and looking back at the first.",
      "This chapter explains how the industry actually works. Trade press is structurally less able to publish what follows; The First Owner’s Reference has no equivalent constraint. Independence here is structural rather than stylistic.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The two parallel commission norms" },
      "A typical brokerage sale of a 40-metre yacht for EUR 28 million moves between EUR 1.4 million and EUR 2.8 million in commissions, depending on which of two parallel norms is applied. Both are presented as \"the standard\" by the brokers using them. They are not the same.",
      "The US norm, IYBA-aligned, is a flat 10 percent of gross sale price, paid by the seller. On a USD 50 million sale, that is USD 5 million. The MYBA sliding scale is 10 percent on the first USD 10 million, 5 percent on the second USD 10 million, 2.5 percent above. On a USD 50 million sale, that is USD 2.25 million. The seller does not always know which is being applied. The buyer almost never knows. The 4 percent or 5 percent of gross sale price typically captured by the buyer's broker, paid out of the seller's commission pool, is the same arithmetic from either base.",
      "Practitioner commentary attributed to Cromwell Littlejohn (Northrop & Johnson, currently President and Chief Commercial Officer) at industry events has acknowledged that brokers can be reluctant to publish non-standard, that is to say reduced, commission rates on the central agency listing, on the basis that disclosure may suppress buyer-broker viewings. The opinion attributed to him is that the system can reward opacity. The First Owner’s Reference offers this as published practitioner opinion rather than as a settled finding, and notes that Northrop & Johnson itself states a commitment to working with full transparency.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Camper & Nicholsons and Fincantieri" },
      "One of the older and largest brokerages in the industry is Camper & Nicholsons. C&N was acquired in 2014 by Coliseum Services SA, a Geneva-based vehicle subsequently renamed the 1782 Group. Lai Sun Development, a Hong Kong real estate group, took an equity stake. In May 2015, the Italian state-controlled shipbuilder Fincantieri acquired a 15 percent minority stake via a capital increase, with Coliseum Services remaining the majority shareholder.",
      "So C&N has, on its capitalisation table, an Italian shipbuilder that builds yachts that C&N then sells. The disclosure of this relationship is not consistently made when C&N markets a Fincantieri-built yacht. The conflict is structural and permanent. The trade press has not, to the publication\u2019s knowledge, investigated it.",
      "The Fincantieri example is the cleanest, but it is not unique. In November 2025, the US private equity firm Ancient (established 2021 by Alexander Klabin, also chairman of Sotheby\u2019s-related investment vehicles and Solairus aviation) acquired a strategic stake in Burgess on undisclosed terms. Burgess\u2019s first outside investor in 50 years; CEO Jonathan Beckett and the senior leadership team remained in place. Fraser and Northrop & Johnson sit inside MarineMax (NYSE: HZO), which acquired both in 2019 and 2020. Denison Yachting was sold by the Denison family in April 2022 to OneWater Marine (NASDAQ: ONEW) and merged into the OneWater Yacht Group in September 2025.",
      "The roll-up is essentially complete. Independent founder-led houses are now the minority by deal volume. The PE owners require EBITDA growth, which incentivises cross-selling more services per yacht, capturing more of the recurring management and refit spend, and consolidating commission pools. The \"free advice\" model is more profitable, not less, under PE ownership.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Dual agency and the IYBA standard form" },
      "The IYBA Purchase and Sale Agreement, the standard contract used in most US-jurisdiction yacht transactions, contains a dual-agency clause that constitutes pre-emptive consent. Signing the standard form means the buyer and seller have already agreed that the broker may act for both sides, with carve-outs (the broker cannot tell the seller the buyer's maximum, cannot tell the buyer the seller's minimum). The standard form normalises a fiduciary impossibility.",
      "In January 2025, Judge K. Michael Moore of the US District Court for the Southern District of Florida dismissed Ya Mon Expeditions LLC v. IYBA et al., a Sherman Act class action alleging conspiracy to fix commissions across the industry. The dismissal was on procedural grounds: insufficient evidence of explicit agreement to fix. The pleadings, which remain on file, document a transaction in which both sides of a sale were brokered by the same firm, with the firm collecting both sides of the 10 percent commission. The case did not establish illegality. It did establish that the practice is sufficiently common and sufficiently questioned to generate federal litigation.",
      "California requires explicit dual-agency disclosure under brokerage law. Florida operates under transactional brokerage rules where full agency duties to either side are diluted by default. The UK Financial Conduct Authority does not regulate yacht sales because they are not a regulated financial instrument. The Maritime and Coastguard Agency does not regulate brokerage commissions. There is no financial regulator anywhere in the major jurisdictions that supervises yacht brokerage conduct.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The system, in published practitioner opinion, can reward opacity.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "Retrocession and the kickback economy" },
      "Referral fees from yacht-management firms, refit yards, paint contractors, electronics integrators, insurance brokers, finance providers, crew agencies, and class societies to the introducing broker are an open secret. OnboardOnline's legal column states the rule plainly: referral fees are legal only if disclosed, must be reflected in the closing statement to seller and buyer, and undisclosed payments to a captain are potentially criminal. There is no equivalent rule that compels the brokerage house to disclose retrocessions on ongoing services to its yacht-owning client.",
      "On a EUR 4 million repaint, a 5 percent retrocession is EUR 200,000. On a EUR 5 million annual management contract, a 10 percent introductory retrocession is EUR 500,000 in year one. The numbers are not small. They are also not on the broker's invoice to the owner because the broker is not invoicing the owner. The owner pays the yard, the management company, the paint contractor; the retrocessions flow inside the supplier's books.",
      "Particular firms are not named in this chapter because the practice is industry-wide and most participants do not consider themselves dishonest. They consider themselves industry-standard. Which they are. The point is structural: when the buyer's adviser earns more if the buyer spends more with counterparties the adviser has steered them toward, the adviser's incentives are not aligned with the buyer's. That structure is the default of the superyacht industry.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The captain's loyalty problem" },
      "The captain is the highest-leverage hire an owner makes. They are also, often, the first hire. The captain is involved in the yacht selection, the survey, the sea trial, the recruitment of the rest of the crew, the choice of management company, the relationships with yards and contractors, and the day-to-day operating budget.",
      "The captain is also a human being with a career and a network. They have worked for other owners, for other yards, for other brokers. They have relationships that long pre-date the owner's involvement. Most captains are honest professionals who do their best for the owner who employs them. A small minority are not. The structure of the role provides ample opportunity for either, and the owner will struggle to tell which they have hired until well after the decision is made.",
      "A useful framework: the captain who tells you what you want to hear in the first three meetings is not the captain you want. The one who pushes back, who asks hard questions about your intended use, who is sceptical of your timeline, is the one to hire. Captains who agree easily are pleasant to work with and expensive to live with.",
      { type: "h2", text: "What independence actually means" },
      "Several firms describe themselves as independent. The word does meaningful work in some cases and is decorative in others. The independence test, set out in full in chapter 9, has six elements.",
      "One: does the firm earn anything contingent on a transaction closing? If yes, they are not independent of the deal. Two: does the firm hold any equity, employment, or referral relationship with any yard, broker, supplier, management company, or charter operation? If yes, they are not independent of those counterparties. Three: does the firm publish a complete list of every counterparty they have worked with in the past three years, with the nature of the relationship? If no, the reader cannot test claims one and two. Four: are the firm's fees transparent and quoted in writing in advance? If no, the structure can hide commissions. Five: does the firm hold professional indemnity insurance at a level appropriate to the transaction? If no, the firm cannot afford to be wrong on the buyer's behalf. Six: are the firm's principals named, traceable, and accountable? If no, none of the above can be verified.",
      "Six questions. Apply them to anyone proposing to advise on the acquisition, including the publisher of The First Owner’s Reference. The publisher's own answers are set out on the colophon.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The honest version of the conversation" },
      "For a reader in advance of a first acquisition, the practical version of the above is this. Engage an independent adviser before engaging a broker. Engage independent legal counsel rather than the broker's preferred firm. Engage an independent surveyor rather than the seller's. Pay all three directly. Consider it the cheapest insurance available. A party who objects to this arrangement has told you something useful about themselves.",
      "The industry will absorb capital regardless of how many advisers a buyer hires. The question is whether it does so on terms the buyer has understood and chosen, or on terms the buyer discovers later. The First Owner’s Reference is written on the assumption that the first option is preferable.",
    ],
  },

  "04-acquisition-process": {
    slug: "04-acquisition-process",
    title: "The acquisition process",
    standfirst:
      "From shortlist to closing in 12 to 24 weeks, with five decision points where most consequential errors are made.",
    readingTime: "7 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "Once the decision to buy has been made, and the right adviser team is in place, the acquisition itself is a 12 to 24 week sequence with a small number of decision points where most of the consequential errors are made. This chapter walks through that sequence and names the five most common pitfalls. The procedural detail is in the back of the print edition; what follows is the analytical frame.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The shortlist" },
      "Most first-time buyers see between 12 and 30 yachts before they shortlist three to five. The visit phase is where brokers add genuine value, because they have walked through the inventory and know what is rough and what is tight. It is also where they extract information about the buyer (budget, intended use, decision timeline, family involvement) that will subsequently shape every recommendation.",
      "Two disciplines protect the shortlist phase. First, do not disclose budget to anyone who earns contingent on a sale closing. Disclose use case, size band, and propulsion preference. Let the broker fit yachts to the use case. The budget conversation belongs with the independent adviser. Second, walk yachts in the company of the independent adviser as well as the broker. The independent adviser is looking for things the broker is not paid to find.",
      "The shortlist itself should be three to five yachts, ideally from at least two brokerages. A shortlist drawn entirely from a single broker's central agency book is structurally limited. The independent adviser can run a parallel scan against the entire market, not just the listings on which the broker earns directly.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Pre-purchase survey" },
      "The pre-purchase survey is the single highest-leverage piece of due diligence in the entire acquisition. It is also the one most commonly compromised by a buyer who is in a rush, in love with the yacht, or relying on the seller's most recent class survey rather than commissioning their own.",
      "A proper pre-purchase survey on a 40m yacht runs 4 to 7 days afloat plus haul-out, costs USD 25,000 to 60,000 depending on scope, and involves an independently-engaged surveyor (not one suggested by the broker), a class society inspector if the yacht is in class, and where appropriate a paint specialist, an electrical and electronics specialist, and a mechanical engineer. Recognised surveyors include Wolfson Marine, Ward & McKenzie, Patton Marine, Winterbothams. The independence test applies: if the broker recommended the surveyor, the surveyor is not independent.",
      "What the survey catches: corrosion, structural issues, paint condition, mechanical wear, electrical compliance, generator and HVAC condition, hull damage history, deck and superstructure issues. What the survey commonly misses: forthcoming class survey costs (the next 5-year survey may be 18 months away), latent design defects masked by patch repairs, hidden modifications to systems, and the complete maintenance history.",
      "The surveyor produces a report with deficiencies categorised by severity. The buyer then has three options: walk away, renegotiate price reflecting the deficiencies, or proceed at original price. The reflexive instinct of inexperienced buyers is to fix small problems for free with the seller. The disciplined response is to renegotiate, because every deficiency the survey did not catch is one the buyer will discover and pay for after closing.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The survey is the moment at which the asymmetry between buyer and seller is most acute. Inexperienced buyers spend it reassuring themselves. Disciplined buyers spend it negotiating.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "Sea trial" },
      "The sea trial happens after the survey, typically on the same yard visit. Standard MOA terms allow 4 to 8 hours of sea trial at the seller's expense. The buyer brings their own captain candidate, surveyor, and a chief engineer if motor and propulsion are central to the use case.",
      "What is being tested: handling at speed and at anchor, stability, vibration, noise levels at various engine loads, navigation electronics, communications systems, autopilot and control systems, comfort underway, and the absence of any failure modes the survey did not catch. Common failures during sea trial include unexpected vibration at certain RPM bands, poor noise insulation in master cabin underway, navigation electronics that the seller's crew has not maintained, and stabilisers that work at one heel angle and not at another.",
      "If the sea trial reveals issues, the price renegotiation continues. If the sea trial reveals nothing, the next step is the closing.",
      { type: "h2", text: "VAT, flag, and registration" },
      "Two procedural choices materially affect the cost of ownership over the next decade and are commonly made under time pressure at closing without proper analysis.",
      "VAT regime. The default is full VAT on purchase: 20 percent in France, 21 percent in Spain, 22 percent in Italy. On a EUR 4 million yacht the bill is EUR 800,000 to EUR 880,000. Three legitimate alternatives reduce or eliminate this. The French Commercial Exemption (FCE) eliminates VAT entirely if six conditions are met (commercial registration, full-time crew, length above 15 metres, more than 70 percent of voyages exiting French waters, less than 50 percent static charters). Spanish Inward Processing Relief suspends 21 percent VAT on refit works for non-EU flagged yachts within an 18-month admission window. The Maltese leasing scheme reduces effective VAT to 5.4 to 6.12 percent on yachts over 24 metres. Italian leasing has been largely curtailed by EU infringement proceedings.",
      "Each option has compliance burden. None should be selected on the broker's preference. Hill Dickinson, Watson Farley & Williams, Ince, Stephenson Harwood, and Reed Smith all publish material on the comparative analysis. Your independent adviser engages one of those firms; they do not engage the broker's preferred counsel.",
      "Flag state. The major options are Cayman Islands, Marshall Islands, Malta, the Red Ensign Group jurisdictions (UK, Isle of Man, Bermuda, Jersey, Guernsey, BVI, Cayman, Gibraltar, Anguilla, Montserrat, Turks and Caicos, Falkland Islands, St Helena, Pitcairn), and a small number of others. The choice depends on owner residence, intended cruising area, charter intent, financing requirements, and the family office's broader structuring preferences. Cayman and Marshall Islands dominate the over-30m segment.",
      "Compliance cost on a 40 metre yacht for tax compliance, structuring, and flag administration runs EUR 50,000 to EUR 150,000 per year. This is recurring opex that does not appear in the broker's headline figures.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Closing" },
      "The closing itself is procedurally straightforward. MYBA Memorandum of Agreement, signed at heads-of-terms with deposit (typically 10 percent), then closing 30 to 60 days later with balance, transfer of title, delivery, and a brief acceptance period (typically 24 to 72 hours) during which the buyer can reject for material non-compliance with specification.",
      "The errors are not at closing. They are upstream. By closing, the buyer has either negotiated the right contract or has not. The right contract has clean title warranties, an inventory matching what was sold, agreed deficiencies remediated or priced, an acceptance protocol that gives the buyer time to verify, and a governing law clause that is not the seller's home jurisdiction.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The five most common pitfalls" },
      "In rough order of frequency:",
      "1. The seller-recommended surveyor. The broker introduces a surveyor whose work the broker knows. The surveyor's report is calibrated for the deal closing. Avoid by engaging your own surveyor through your independent adviser.",
      "2. The closing rush. The seller indicates that another buyer is interested, or that the slot at the marina is being lost, or that the prices in the brokerage market are about to move. Closing acceleration is almost always the seller's interest, not the buyer's. Three weeks of additional due diligence costs nothing and saves significantly.",
      "3. Inadequate pre-purchase survey scope. The buyer accepts a surveyor's quote that excludes paint condition, electronics, or full mechanical inspection because the seller's recent class survey \"covered it.\" Class surveys are not buyer-side surveys. They are not designed to find the things you want to know.",
      "4. VAT regime defaulted to broker recommendation. The broker's preferred VAT structure is the one their preferred lawyer has the relationship to deliver. It may not be the right structure for your use pattern. The VAT decision is worth a separate legal opinion from your own counsel.",
      "5. Closing without a competent technical handover. The seller's captain knows the yacht. The buyer's captain (often newly hired) does not. A formal technical handover with both captains and the chief engineer present, lasting 3 to 5 days, surfaces issues that a paper specification does not. Skipping it is the single most expensive false economy in the entire acquisition.",
      "A buyer who avoids these five pitfalls will not have bought a perfect yacht. They will have bought one whose flaws they understand. That is the right standard for a first acquisition.",
    ],
  },

  "05-new-build-versus-brokerage": {
    slug: "05-new-build-versus-brokerage",
    title: "New build versus brokerage",
    standfirst:
      "The decision is framed in trade press as a matter of taste. It is a matter of risk profile, capital commitment timing, and the quality of the buyer's representation.",
    readingTime: "14 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "The new build versus brokerage decision is framed in trade press as a matter of taste. Custom expression versus immediate availability. Bespoke versus practical. This framing is wrong. The decision is a matter of risk profile, capital commitment timing, and the quality of the buyer's representation. The financial and operational consequences of the choice diverge sharply over the next decade. This chapter makes that case.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The two paths, honestly described" },
      "Brokerage acquisition is the purchase of an existing yacht from an existing owner. Time from offer to delivery is typically 6 to 12 weeks. Capital commitment is concentrated at closing. The yacht is a known quantity (insofar as the survey reveals it). The buyer takes the seller's specification, the seller's build quality, the seller's wear and tear, and the seller's accumulated maintenance debt. The risk profile is read once, at survey, and accepted.",
      "New build is the commissioning of a yacht to specification from a shipyard. Time from contract to delivery is 24 to 36 months for semi-custom and 36 to 60 months for fully custom. Capital is committed in stage payments across the build, typically 20 to 30 percent at signature, 50 to 70 percent across the build, balance at delivery. The yacht is bespoke; everything from the hull form to the door handles is specified by the owner and the design team. The risk profile is open across the entire build window.",
      "The cost premium of new build over a comparable brokerage hull is typically 30 to 50 percent at the entry of the curve, narrowing to 15 to 25 percent at delivery as the brokerage hull depreciates and the new build hits the market. Over a five-year hold, the gap closes further, and quality builders (Feadship, Lurssen, Royal Huisman, Vitters) hold value materially better than brokerage acquisitions of comparable size.",
      "The commercial case for new build is therefore not \"it costs more but it's worth it for the customisation.\" It is that for a buyer with a 7 to 10 year hold horizon, an intended use pattern that depends on bespoke specification, and access to a competent representation team, new build is sometimes the lower total cost decision over the hold period, despite a higher headline price. For a buyer without those three conditions, new build is materially worse.",
      { type: "h2", text: "What goes wrong in new build" },
      "The published evidence on new build dispute is dominated by buyer-side governance failures. Three documented cases illustrate the pattern.",
      "REV Ocean, a research and expedition vessel under construction by Vard (a Fincantieri subsidiary) at Aalesund and S\u00f8viknes for the Norwegian industrialist Kjell Inge R\u00f8kke, with Espen Oeino as designer, was originally targeted for delivery in 2021. The project paused 2021 to 2023 over published technical and weight issues against the shipbuilding contract specification. The vessel is being lengthened by 12 metres and modified to bring it into compliance, with outfitting now contracted to Damen Shiprepair and revised delivery in late 2026 to 2027. This is a yard-side performance dispute, not a buyer-side governance failure, and it is worth citing as illustration of contract performance issues generally.",
      "Project Somnio, the 222 metre residential vessel project associated with Carl Le Souef and Captain Erik Bredhe, generated a UK High Court ruling in January 2025 (Winch Design Limited v Le Souef [2025] EWHC 120 (Comm)) that Le Souef was personally liable for GBP 733,750 in unpaid invoices to Winch Design. Le Souef had argued the contract was with Somnio Superyachts Pty Limited, an SPV. The court determined that any objective bystander would have read the contract as identifying Le Souef himself as the contracting party, and dismissed the rectification argument for lack of evidence of a shared intention to contract through the SPV. This is the buyer-side governance failure: an owner contracting personally without proper structuring, or with structuring that did not survive litigation.",
      "The Italian Sea Group restructuring of April 2026, in which the Court of Florence granted four-month protection through 16 July 2026 specifically preventing shipowners from terminating in-build contracts during the restructuring window, illustrates the third risk: the yard\u2019s own financial distress. The order implies multiple in-build clients were ready to walk. The buyer who signed a contract with a yard later in financial distress had the yard\u2019s interests prioritised over their own through a court order.",
      "These are the published cases. Most disputes settle privately under London Maritime Arbitrators Association confidentiality and never produce a public award. The published record is enough to make the point.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Yards going under, owners holding the bag" },
      "There is a separate pattern, less covered in trade press, that has emerged across the past five years. A yard runs into financial difficulty mid-build. The owner is presented with a choice that is not really a choice: inject additional capital, sometimes as equity in the restructured business, in order to see the yacht delivered, or face the prospect of the yacht stalling, the supplier chain freezing, and the work-in-progress becoming an asset of the insolvency rather than a yacht under construction.",
      "Nobiskrug, the German builder of Sailing Yacht A and a number of other large hulls, is the cleanest recent example. The yard, then under the Tennor Group ownership of Lars Windhorst, filed for insolvency in December 2024 alongside Flensburger Schiffbau-Gesellschaft (FSG). Lurssen submitted an offer to acquire the Nobiskrug assets and the acquisition completed in early 2025, with the yard integrated into the neighbouring Lurssen-Kr\u00f6ger facility and over 95 percent of the combined Nobiskrug and FSG workforce transferring under a transfer-company mechanism. Suspended in-build projects, including a 62 metre yacht, were moved to Lurssen facilities for completion. Owners with hulls in the yard at the point of insolvency faced direct exposure: contracts had to be novated to the acquiring entity, terms renegotiated, and in some cases owners were asked for additional payments to cover trustee costs the original yard had quoted under terms no longer in force. The principal who imagined the contract held the price quoted at signature found that insolvency law sits above the contract.",
      "Italian Sea Group\u2019s April 2026 restructuring (operating brands include Admiral, Tecnomar, Perini Navi, Picchiotti and the NCA refit operation) extended the same logic into procedural protection. On 20 April 2026 the Court of Florence confirmed protective measures retroactive to the 16 March filing date for a maximum of four months, until 16 July 2026. The order extends explicitly to shipowners with vessels in build at TISG yards, preventing them from terminating in-build contracts during the restructuring window. From the buyer\u2019s perspective it was a court-mandated commitment to a counterparty whose financial condition had changed since signature; from the yard\u2019s perspective it was the breathing room necessary to negotiate the restructuring with creditors.",
      "The pattern in both cases is the same. The buyer pays stage payments forward, expecting the yard to convert them into hull, machinery, and outfit. When the yard\u2019s financial condition deteriorates, the buyer\u2019s stage payments become creditor positions in someone else\u2019s insolvency. Refund guarantees protect a portion of the exposure, in principle; the practical operation of those guarantees, particularly under non-tier-one bank wrappers, is less reliable than the contract suggests. Norton Rose Fulbright\u2019s commentary on Chinese-bank refund guarantees expiring within one month of cancellation is widely cited; the specific yard\u2019s insolvency moves at procedural pace; the timing rarely lines up.",
      "What this means for a first-time buyer. First, yard financial due diligence at heads of terms is not optional. Recent published accounts, parent company structure, order book composition, and any litigation history are part of the standard pre-contract assessment. Second, refund guarantee credit quality matters as much as any other contract term. Third, the buyer should anticipate that, if the yard does run into trouble during the build, the buyer will be presented with an equity-injection or accelerated-payment option framed as the only route to delivery. Whether to accept is a decision worth making in advance, with counsel, rather than under pressure.",
      "There is a second variant of yard equity that is worth distinguishing from the distress case. Some smaller, founder-led yards offer customers an equity position in the building entity as part of the contract structure, on the basis that the alignment is mutually beneficial. Pendennis Shipyard is the practitioner reference for this approach, although the firm does not publish the structure. The mechanism, where it works, is structural rather than reactive: the buyer holds a minority equity position in the yard for the duration of the build, the yard is incentivised to deliver to specification, and any yard underperformance is partially absorbed at equity level rather than entirely at customer level. The arrangement is not common and is rarely available to first-time buyers, but it exists. The structural test for any such arrangement is the same as the distress case in reverse: does the equity position align the yard\u2019s incentives with the buyer\u2019s, and does it survive scrutiny by counsel as a matter of corporate governance and tax structure rather than as a marketing wrapper.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The new build contract is where inexperience gets priced. The cost overrun appears later, but it was paid for at signature.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "The contract is where it happens" },
      "A new build contract is the most consequential document a yacht buyer signs. It governs USD 30 to USD 200 million of capital across two to five years, and structures every variation, every dispute, every interpretation question in the period during which the yard holds the cards.",
      "Top-tier yards do not contract on industry-standard forms. The MYBA Memorandum of Agreement is the dominant standard for second-hand sale, not new construction. Standard shipbuilding forms exist (the Shipbuilders' Association of Japan SAJ form, the Association of Western European Shipbuilders AWES form, BIMCO's NEWBUILDCON, the Norwegian SHIP 2000) and are summarised in Robert Jardine-Brown's Chambers commentary. SAJ is most used globally and \"thought to favour the shipyard\" in unamended form. But the European yards that matter (Lurssen, Feadship, Oceanco, Royal Huisman, Heesen, Sanlorenzo, Benetti) do not contract on any of those. They contract on heavily customised in-house templates drafted by their counsel, with English law and London arbitration grafted on.",
      "Hannaford Turner partner Justin Turner notes engagement typically begins at request-for-proposal stage, not after head terms are signed. The buyer who does not retain specialist shipbuilding counsel before signing is being asked to negotiate a bespoke document drafted entirely by the yard's lawyers, against a body of standard forms the buyer's representative has likely never seen.",
      "Ten specific points an inexperienced representative gives away at signature:",
      "1. Stage payment loading. Shipbuilding industry typical: 50 to 70 percent of contract value paid before delivery (Watson Farley & Williams). Aggressive front-loading suggests the yard is short of cash to start the build.",
      "2. Refund guarantee credit quality. Tier-one bank pay-on-demand guarantees are materially better than surety wrappers. Chinese-bank refund guarantees commonly expire one month or less after cancellation, forcing immediate arbitration (Norton Rose Fulbright).",
      "3. Liquidated damages cap. Industry typical: 1 percent of contract value per week of delay, capped at 5 to 10 percent of contract sum. After the cap, the yard owes nothing further (Hill Dickinson, citing Triple Point Technology v PTT [2021] UKSC 29).",
      "4. Force majeure burden. English law requires the yard to prove \"but for\" causation under Classic Maritime v Limbungan [2019] EWCA Civ 1102. Yards routinely write looser clauses; weak reps accept them.",
      "5. Change order procedure. Without a defined procedure with pre-agreed unit rates and third-party quote rights, \"the owner is open to being forced to pay for change orders or emergent work at a unit rate much higher than in the original contract\" (Stephenson Harwood, Sean Gibbons).",
      "6. Defect notification deadlines. Typically 14 days from discovery, with failure to notify potentially extinguishing the claim entirely (HFW).",
      "7. Warranty length. Standard 12 months. Negotiable to 24. Most inexperienced reps do not negotiate it.",
      "8. Cancellation thresholds. SAJ standard: 150 days post-delivery date or 180 days total delay (Jiangsu Guoxin v Precious Shipping [2020] EWHC 1030). Bespoke yacht contracts replicate but with negotiable thresholds.",
      "9. Title position during construction. Some yards (Feadship cited) retain title until delivery; others transfer progressively. This determines who carries insolvency risk and who has repossession rights.",
      "10. Dispute forum. English law plus LMAA arbitration is the practitioner default. Inexperienced reps sometimes accept non-English law or non-LMAA seats that materially weaken the buyer's position.",
      "A single afternoon's competent legal review at heads-of-terms saves more than the owner's representative fee for the entire project. It is consistently not done.",
      { type: "h2", text: "SYBAss founded YORP because the gap was structural" },
      "The Superyacht Builders Association, with the International Association of Maritime Institutions and the GUEST guild for chief stewards, launched the Yacht Owner Representative Programme (YORP) in July 2023. Four courses, 200 hours, founding member Benetti; the first pilot course ran 24 to 28 July 2023 at Benetti Yachts Livorno. In November 2024 the Yacht Owner\u2019s Representative Register (YORR) followed, administered by the Superyacht Alliance for Professional Standards in Malta. CV audit \u201cto eliminate inflated CVs.\u201d Code of conduct. Theo Hooning, then SYBAss Secretary General, on the launch: \u201cas yachting becomes increasingly professionalised, there has been a corresponding recognition of the importance of proper training.\u201d",
      "The institutional movement is the story. SYBAss member yards include Lurssen, Feadship, Oceanco, Heesen, Royal Huisman, Vitters, Baltic Yachts, Abeking & Rasmussen, Royal Falcon, Codecasa, CRN, Benetti, Sanlorenzo. Collectively roughly two thirds of yachts over 40 metres in build. They do not stand up an industry register without a problem they want fixed.",
      "The strongest single anecdote on the published record comes from Jack Inglis, who runs the independent owner's representative firm ULTIMAR. Writing in Superyacht Investor: a semi-custom new build where the owner deputised a family office CFO with no maritime expertise as the owner's representative. The delivery snag list exceeded 1,200 items. The family office had reported around 100. Safety, technical, and interior issues missed because the rep did not know what to look for. Inglis's framing: vessels poorly overseen during construction \"return back to the yards for warranty works quicker than they are delivered.\"",
      "Yard-side voices have been measured but consistent in published interviews. Tony Gale, CEO of ICON Yachts, has spoken in BOAT International coverage published September 2025 about the value to a yard of working with a professional owner-side team that brings clarity to the brief and to project execution. Tim Kershaw at Dunya Yachts and Richie Blake at Doehle Yachts have made similar published comments about owner-side professionalism being a yard benefit as well as an owner one, and about the operational difficulty of dealing with owner-side representatives who lack the appropriate disposition. Kevin Laverty, Director of Projects at Hill Robinson, has discussed in Hill Robinson and BOAT International commentary the relative thinness of yacht-construction contracts as drafted, with one widely cited example a 33-page contract for a 77 metre yacht against the multi-volume documentation typical of oil and gas projects of comparable cost. Each of these voices is offered as published practitioner opinion rather than as a final settled view.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The owner's representative market" },
      "The independent owner's representative market is structurally undersized and structurally conflicted. Genuinely independent firms, paid only by the owner, with no broker commission and no yard affiliation, are a small group. They include A2B Marine Projects, ULTIMAR, Divergent Yachting, Mariner Technical Services, Praxis Marine, JMS Yachting, ABL Yachts, KRM Yacht, Saor Alba, Occam Naval Architecture and Project Management, and the publisher of The First Owner’s Reference.",
      "Brokerage houses with new build arms include Edmiston, Burgess, Y.CO, Ocean Independence, Camper & Nicholsons, Fraser, Cecil Wright, and Moran. Burgess Technical Services markets itself as offering \"independent, objective oversight\" while Burgess is one of the largest brokerages globally. Cecil Wright topped the Spear's 2025 Yacht Advisers ranking and acted as owner's representative on the 83m Feadship Project Solent; Cecil Wright is a broker. The dual-role conflict is structurally identical at every scale.",
      "Yacht management companies extending into new build include Hill Robinson, Doehle Yachts Technical Services, and Wright Maritime Group. Naval architects acting as owner's representatives include Vitruvius (Briand), Reymond Langton, Espen Oeino, Bannenberg & Rowell, Andrew Winch, and Newcruise. The naval architect conflict is in mirror to the broker conflict: the design firm has a continuing commercial relationship with the yard.",
      "Family-office-focused entrants are post-2023, including Ikonic Yachts (founded 2023), Superyacht Partners, Praxis Group, Oak Group, and Morpho Luxury Asset Management.",
      "The fee structures of the major firms (Edmiston, Burgess, Cecil Wright, Y.CO, Moran, Hill Robinson) are not published. Independent firms, including the publisher of The First Owner’s Reference, also rarely publish percentages. Anecdotal practitioner range for genuinely independent firms is 1 to 3 percent of build cost, or fixed fees in the EUR 1 million to EUR 3 million range over a 36-month build on a EUR 100 million project. Brokers acting as owner's representatives are typically paid by yard commission of around 5 percent. The dual-role firms therefore make more from the buyer's side without disclosing it. The lack of published fee structures across the entire owner's representative market is itself a finding.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The decision" },
      "For a buyer considering new build, the threshold tests are these.",
      "First, do you have a 7 to 10 year hold horizon? If not, brokerage. The new build cost premium does not amortise over a shorter hold.",
      "Second, is your intended use pattern materially specific to the yacht (size, layout, propulsion, range, operational profile)? If a brokerage hull within a reasonable search window can deliver 80 percent of your use case, brokerage. Custom is for the residual 20 percent that genuinely matters.",
      "Third, can you commit to the team-building discipline that new build requires? Independent owner\u2019s representative engaged before contract, specialist shipbuilding counsel from a top firm, technical due diligence on the yard\u2019s current order book and financial condition, and a willingness to push back against the yard\u2019s first-draft contract on every point that matters. If commitment to all four is not in place, brokerage tends to be the calmer path.",
      "If those three threshold tests are positive, new build at a SYBAss member yard is one of the great purchases a UHNW principal can make. Without those conditions, it tends to be one of the more expensive ways to acquire a yacht. The case in this chapter is for the conditions, not against the path.",
    ],
  },

  "06-refit": {
    slug: "06-refit",
    title: "Refit",
    standfirst:
      "Where ownership cost concentrates, where ownership quality is renewed, and where the owner-yard relationship is most often dysfunctional.",
    readingTime: "15 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "A yacht's life is divided into refit cycles. Every five years a class survey forces structural and systems work. Every ten years the cosmetic and major systems condition demands a substantive overhaul. Refit is where ownership cost concentrates, where ownership quality is renewed, and where the relationship between owner, yard, and project manager is most often dysfunctional.",
      "The global refit market was sized at USD 2.9 billion in 2025 supporting roughly 6,000 active vessels requiring regular major works (Future Market Insights). Capacity has expanded modestly while the fleet has grown substantially. The result is tightening lead times at the established yards and a refit market that has become, in 2026, a sellers' market for the first time in a decade.",
      { type: "h2", text: "When to refit, when to sell" },
      "The decision to refit a yacht assumes the owner intends to continue owning it. For a 12 to 15 year old yacht facing a major refit, the alternative is sale and reacquisition. The sale yields capital. The refit consumes capital. The arithmetic of which is better depends on three variables: the yacht's strategic fit with the owner's continued use case, the cost of a comparable replacement, and the depreciation profile of the post-refit hull versus the alternative.",
      "A useful rule: if the projected refit cost exceeds 30 percent of the yacht's pre-refit market value, and the owner has not made a clear decision that this particular yacht is not replaceable for their use case, sale is usually the better decision. Below 30 percent, refit is normally the better decision. The threshold is rough; the calculation is bespoke.",
      "The owner who refits a yacht the wrong side of that threshold is taking on a project whose total cost is materially higher than the post-refit yacht's market value. The owner who sells a yacht for which they have a strategic fit, on the basis that \"the refit was looking expensive,\" will spend more on the replacement and lose continuity of crew and operation that takes years to rebuild.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Refit cost benchmarks" },
      "A five-year survey or major refit typically runs 5 to 15 percent of insured hull value, depending on scope. Working ranges per metre per year, derived from a practitioner project archive of more than 30 managed refit projects:",
      "Annual maintenance: EUR 2,000 to 8,000 per metre. Mid-life refit: EUR 10,000 to 30,000 per metre. Major structural refit: EUR 40,000 to 100,000+ per metre.",
      "A 50m yacht with a major structural refit therefore sits in the EUR 2 million to EUR 5 million range, with USD 5 million to 10 million being typical for full-scope projects involving extension, re-engining, or substantial cosmetic and systems renewal.",
      "Mediterranean berth fees during refit run EUR 400 to 800 per day for a 40 metre hull. Northern Europe berth fees run EUR 600 to 1,200. Mediterranean skilled labour runs EUR 45 to 75 per hour with specialists at EUR 80 to 120. Northern Europe runs 20 to 40 percent more across both labour categories.",
      "These numbers are well-evidenced from project archives but not from published yard rate cards. MB92 and Pendennis do not publish day rates. The numbers in this chapter are within the working ranges that practitioners across the industry would recognise.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The 30 to 50 percent overrun is not a project management failure. It is the empirical expectation.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "The 30 to 50 percent overrun pattern" },
      "Industry consensus is that refit projects routinely run 30 to 50 percent over original quoted scope. The pattern is well-rehearsed in trade press. Practitioner consensus from independent owner's representatives points to the same range, with poor specification and weak project management as the dominant drivers. Dockwalk documented a 600 percent overrun on a 1967 Camper & Nicholsons refit (USD 1 million budget, USD 6 million actual, an extreme case but illustrative). The contingency reserves practitioners build into refit budgets reflect this: 10 to 15 percent for known scope, 15 to 20 percent for opened-up vessels, 20 to 25 percent for first-time-opened older hulls.",
      "The honest framing for first-time owners: the 30 to 50 percent overrun is not a project management failure. It is the empirical expectation against an initial scope that is built on imperfect information. A refit yard quote based on visual inspection cannot anticipate everything that will be found when the deck is opened, the engine room is stripped, or the bilges are scrubbed. Discovered work is real. The question is not whether the refit will run over scope. The question is by how much, and whether the structure of the refit contract and the discipline of the owner's representation contains the overrun within reason.",
      "A well-managed refit at a competent yard with experienced owner-side representation typically lands within 10 to 20 percent of original quote. A poorly-managed refit can land at the extremes documented above. The variance is mostly explained by the quality of the owner's representation.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Two yard models, both worth understanding" },
      "There are two structural models in the refit market and the difference between them shapes everything that follows. Full-service yards take the project on as a single contract, manage the trades in-house, and deliver the yacht at an agreed milestone. Service yards (also called marina yards or non-full-service yards) provide the facility, the haul-out, and the infrastructure, while the owner contracts the trades directly through the project manager. The same metre of dock can be billed very differently depending on which model is in use.",
      "STP Palma (Servicios T\u00e9cnicos Portuarios), in the Port of Palma, is the best-known example of the service-yard model. Owners and their project managers contract the trades (paint, mechanical, electrical, joinery) directly with the resident specialists; STP provides the haul-out, the hardstand, and the perimeter services. The model rewards experienced project management and tends to suit owners who want full visibility of every contract line. Lauderdale Marine Center and parts of Marina Port Vell Barcelona operate on similar lines.",
      "Full-service yards (MB92, Pendennis, Lusben, Astilleros de Mallorca, Amico & Co, Rybovich) carry the integration risk and price for it. Service yards (STP, LMC, Marina Port Vell, sections of Astilleros de Mallorca) shift integration responsibility to the owner-side team and are typically less expensive at the line-item level for owners with capable project management. Neither model is structurally better. The right one depends on the buyer\u2019s representation, the scope of the project, and the buyer\u2019s tolerance for direct contract management.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Refit yard capacity in 2026" },
      "The over-30m refit market is concentrated in four geographies: Western Mediterranean (Spain, France, Italy), Northern Europe (UK, Netherlands, Germany), Eastern Mediterranean (Turkey), and the US Eastern Seaboard. Most large-yacht refits land at one of the named yards below.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Western Mediterranean" },
      "MB92 Group. Barcelona plus La Ciotat (acquired Compositeworks and Monaco Marine Golfe-Juan). Also owns the paint specialist GYG, parent of Pinmar, acquired in a transaction completed on 31 December 2024. The dominant full-service Western Mediterranean operator. Pepe Garcia-Aubert, CEO. The Luxembourg-based investment firm Squircle Capital first took a 77.5 percent stake in 2019, raised it to 93 percent in 2022 and 98 percent in 2025, and reached 100 percent ownership in 2025.",
      "Astilleros de Mallorca. Palma. Full-service. 78,000 square metre site. 1,700 tonne haul, 120 metre outfitting quay. Over 250 yachts per year. The reference Spanish full-service yard for over-50m refits.",
      "STP Palma (Servicios T\u00e9cnicos Portuarios). Palma. Service yard model. The owner contracts the trades directly through the project manager. The largest non-full-service refit facility in the Western Mediterranean by yacht throughput.",
      "Marina Port Vell. Barcelona. Mixed full-service and service-yard provision; OneOcean group ownership.",
      "Monaco Marine. Saint Mandrier and Beaulieu, with smaller sites in Antibes and La Ciotat. French full-service refit, repaint, and mechanical work, particularly strong on the 30 to 60m segment.",
      "IMS Shipyard. La Seyne sur Mer (Toulon). French full-service yard, 220m drydock, capable of large refit work and recently expanded.",
      "Lusben. Italy. Viareggio plus Livorno. 76,000 square metre site. 210 metre dry dock, 2,000 tonne syncrolift, 150 tonne travel lift. Capacity 20m to 140m. Livorno yard expanded with a 2,400 tonne syncrolift in 2024 to 2025. The reference Italian full-service yard for large hulls.",
      "Amico & Co. Genoa. Italian full-service yard with a strong reputation on superyacht refit, paint, and mechanical work. Manuel Di Tillio, CEO.",
      "Cantiere Rossini. Marina di Carrara. Italian yard, scaled into superyacht refit capability over the past decade.",
      "Versilia Yachting Rendez-Vous yards. The Viareggio cluster includes refit capacity at Codecasa, Picchiotti, and others, in addition to Lusben.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Northern Europe" },
      "Pendennis Shipyard. Falmouth, UK. Mike Carr, CEO. Completed approximately 18 projects in 2024, well above its annual average of around 10. Throughput rising into capacity. Particularly strong on sailing yacht refits.",
      "Damen Shipyards Group. Vlissingen and other Dutch sites. Full-service refit alongside new build.",
      "Royal Huisman, Vitters, Holland Jachtbouw, Royal Van Lent (Feadship). Northern European builders that take their own hulls back for refit; limited third-party refit capacity but the standard for owners holding those hulls.",
      "Bl\u00e4sing Yacht Service / Lurssen Refit. German full-service refit for the largest yachts.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Eastern Mediterranean" },
      "RMK Marine. Tuzla, Istanbul. Turkish full-service yard with capacity for refit and new build of yachts to around 80m. Public capacity data thin but practitioner reputation strong on cost.",
      "Bilgin Yachts. Tuzla, Istanbul. Yacht builder with refit capability on its own and third-party hulls.",
      "Sirena Marine. Bursa. Builder with refit capacity, particularly on Turkish-built hulls.",
      "Antalya Free Zone yards. Several mid-tier facilities serving the Eastern Mediterranean and Black Sea fleets.",
      { type: "h2", text: "US Eastern Seaboard" },
      "The American market accounts for 45 to 50 percent of brokerage transactions in 2025, on BOAT International data. The refit infrastructure has expanded substantially over the past decade. The principal yards:",
      "Rybovich. West Palm Beach, Florida. Full-service. The reference US yard for large-yacht refit, repaint, and mechanical work. Acquired by Safe Harbor Marinas (Sun Communities) in recent years.",
      "Lauderdale Marine Center (LMC). Fort Lauderdale, Florida. Service yard model on a large scale; the largest yacht refit facility on the US East Coast by yacht throughput. Owners contract trades directly through their project managers.",
      "Bradford Marine. Fort Lauderdale, Florida (and Grand Bahama). Full-service refit, repaint, and mechanical work.",
      "Derecktor Shipyards. Fort Pierce, Florida. Full-service yard expanded substantially over the past five years; recently completed projects include the largest refit haul-outs on the US East Coast.",
      "Roscioli Yachting Center. Dania Beach, Florida. Mid-tier full-service yard, particularly strong on the 30 to 50m segment.",
      "Merrill-Stevens Dry Dock. Miami, Florida. Historic full-service yard recently rebuilt and expanded.",
      "Front Street Shipyard. Belfast, Maine. Full-service yard for refit and new builds up to roughly 60m. The reference yard for high-quality work in the Northeast US.",
      "Newport Shipyard. Newport, Rhode Island. Full-service refit and yacht services on Narragansett Bay; particularly strong during the New England racing season.",
      "Lyman-Morse. Thomaston, Maine. Builder and refit yard, particularly strong on sailing and composite hulls.",
      "Hodgdon Yachts. East Boothbay, Maine. Builder with refit capability on the largest US-built sailing yachts.",
      "Jarrett Bay Boatworks. Beaufort, North Carolina. Refit and repaint yard, particularly strong on sportfish and motor yachts under 40m.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Capacity tightness, in 2026" },
      "The Superyacht Group\u2019s 2025 expert roundtable (Manuel Di Tillio of Amico & Co, Gianni Paladino of Lusben, Txema Rubio of MB92) is the cleanest single source on refit capacity tightness in the Mediterranean and is paywalled. The public-source signal is consistent: fleet up 38.7 percent over the past decade against modestly expanding refit capacity. Lead times for the top European yards are typically booked 12 to 24 months ahead for major refits. US East Coast lead times are shorter on average but tightening, particularly at Rybovich and Derecktor.",
      "For a first-time owner planning a refit in 2027 or 2028, the practical implication is that yard slot booking begins 12 to 18 months before the work itself, and the yard chosen materially affects the cost, quality, and timeline of the project. The cheapest yard is rarely the best decision. The yard most aligned with the type of work, with a track record on similar yachts, with a project manager who has handled comparable scope, is.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Spanish IPR and the VAT economics of refit" },
      "For non-EU flagged yachts, Spanish Inward Processing Relief (IPR), also called Temporary Admission Procedure (TPA), is the most consequential VAT structure available for refit work in EU waters.",
      "The mechanism: a non-EU flagged yacht enters Spanish waters under temporary admission. Refit work is performed at a customs-site shipyard. Spanish 21 percent VAT on the works is suspended during the 18-month admission window (extendable to 24 months under bonded conditions). The yacht is subsequently re-exported. The VAT is never paid.",
      "On a EUR 5 million refit, the saving is approximately EUR 1.05 million. The compliance burden is real (customs site shipyard, bonded works, documentation, re-export evidence) but the saving more than justifies it. MB92, Astilleros de Mallorca, and several smaller Spanish yards are equipped for IPR work.",
      "The Maltese leasing scheme reduces effective VAT to 5.4 to 6.12 percent on yachts over 24 metres. The French Commercial Exemption eliminates VAT entirely on refit if the six conditions are met. Italian commercial exemption similarly. Each has compliance burden. The decision should be informed by a yacht lawyer with VAT specialism, not by the yard's preferred counsel.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The insurance interaction" },
      "The August 2024 sinking of Bayesian off Sicily, with the loss of seven lives and roughly USD 150 million in insured loss, prompted speculation in trade press of broad insurance market hardening. Pantaenius's Michelle van der Merwe stated explicitly: \"I think everyone thought it was going to have more of an impact than it did.\" The actual market response was selective. Tighter clauses on crew qualifications, on stability and battery management, but not blanket rate rises.",
      "The earlier hardening (AIG cited 50 to 70 percent premium increases across 2022 to 2023 in the London market) had already stabilised by H1 2024. By Q4 2025, hull rates were softening 4 to 7.5 percent for fleets with good loss records. The typical hull rate band for a well-maintained 40 to 50 metre yacht: 0.7 to 1.5 percent of insured value annually. Smaller superyachts and yachts in hurricane-exposed regions can pay 2 to 5 percent.",
      "For a refit project, the relevant insurance is builder's risk during the works, not the cruising hull policy. Builder's risk is taken out by the yard with the buyer's interest noted, covering loss or damage during construction up to delivery. The buyer should verify named-insured status, deductible, and that the policy covers transit between subcontractor sites.",
      { type: "h2", text: "What \u201csuperyacht standard\u201d should actually mean" },
      "\u201cSuperyacht standard\u201d is the phrase the trade routinely deploys to describe finishes, tolerances, and workmanship that are, in practice, vaguely defined and easily disputed. The contract that says the work will be carried out \u201cto superyacht standard\u201d is a contract that has not been written. The disciplined refit specification cites the manufacturer\u2019s data sheet, the relevant ISO standard, or both. Nine specifics every serious specification should name:",
      "Paint dry film thickness (DFT). Awlgrip and Alexseal manufacturer technical data sheets define the DFT range for each coat. A typical Awlgrip topcoat system is around 75 to 125 microns DFT per coat, with total system thickness of 200 to 450 microns depending on substrate and coat schedule. The contract should cite the manufacturer data sheet by version and require gauge measurements at agreed intervals.",
      "Paint application conditions. Manufacturer data sheets specify ambient temperature (typically 18 to 29\u00b0C for Awlgrip topcoat), relative humidity (typically below 80 percent), and surface temperature at least 3\u00b0C above the dew point. Spray cells with controlled atmosphere are the only way to maintain these consistently; the contract should require atmospheric logging.",
      "Drying and recoat windows. Awlcraft 2000, Awlgrip Awlbrite, and equivalent Alexseal topcoats specify minimum and maximum recoat windows in hours at given temperature and humidity. The contract should reference the manufacturer\u2019s table by version and require sign-off at each recoat point.",
      "Vibration. ISO 6954:2000 and ISO 20283-5 are the marine vibration standards. Acceptable shipboard vibration is typically expressed in mm per second RMS at the relevant frequency band. Drivetrain vibration tolerances are also specified by the engine and gearbox manufacturers (MTU, Caterpillar, MAN, Rolls-Royce, ZF) in the engine technical data. The contract should cite both the ISO standard and the engine manufacturer figure.",
      "Noise levels. ISO 6954 and the IMO MSC.337(91) noise code apply to crew areas; owner cabins are typically held to tighter limits. Master cabin underway: 45 to 50 dB(A) at design cruising speed is the practitioner standard. Engine room and tender garage limits are specified separately. The contract should require noise mapping at sea trials.",
      "Whole-body vibration in occupied spaces. ISO 2631 sets the comfort limits. Practitioner targets at master cabin underway and at anchor are typically below 0.315 m/s\u00b2 RMS in the relevant frequency band. The sea trial protocol should test against this.",
      "HVAC. ISO 7547 gives the design conditions for ship air conditioning. Manufacturer data sheets (Heinen & Hopman, Westmar, Drews Marine) specify duct velocity limits (typically below 2.5 to 3.0 m/s in occupied spaces to control noise) and air change rates. The contract should cite both.",
      "Hydraulic and stabilisation. Quantum, Naiad, ABT-TRAC, Veem stabiliser manufacturer data sheets set the operational envelope and the noise emission limits. Hydraulic pump and motor noise should be specified in dB(A) at the equipment, and the equipment should be installed on isolation mounts whose specification is agreed in writing.",
      "Surface preparation and substrate condition. Before paint goes on, the substrate must be inspected. The contract should require holiday testing on metallic substrates, profile measurement on prepared steel (typically Sa 2.5 cleanliness, 50 to 75 micron profile), and humidity-controlled conditions during preparation. Skipping this is the most common cause of premature paint failure in the year-three to year-seven window.",
      "The disciplined contract names each of these in writing, with manufacturer data sheet versions and ISO standard editions cited. The phrase \u201csuperyacht standard\u201d does not appear. The reason is contractual rather than aesthetic. \u201cSuperyacht standard\u201d cannot be enforced: there is no objective referent against which a finding of non-compliance can be made, which means the buyer has no clean route to remedy when work falls short. A specification that cites Awlgrip TDS revision X, ISO 6954:2000, or IMO MSC.337(91) gives the buyer, the surveyor, and any subsequent arbitrator something to measure against. Specifications written this way reduce dispute, accelerate sign-off, support warranty claims at the warranty window, and tend to produce a delivery record that holds up under any subsequent insurance, sale, or refit conversation.",
      { type: "h2", text: "How to get a refit right" },
      "Three disciplines distinguish well-managed refits from disasters.",
      "First, scope discipline. Define the work in writing before the contract is signed, with specific deliverables, materials, and finishes, and the named manufacturer and ISO references above. The vague clause is the source of the overrun. Project managers who insist on detailed scope at the start are more expensive to engage and considerably cheaper across the project.",
      "Second, milestone payments. Tie payments to defined deliverables (paint cells completed to specification, engine reinstall completed and vibration measured, sea trials passed against the named noise and vibration limits) rather than to calendar dates. The yard delivers when the milestone delivers, not when the calendar runs out.",
      "Third, weekly site presence. The owner\u2019s representative on site for at least one day per week through the works. The discipline of weekly reporting, with photographs and snag lists, surfaces issues at the point they can still be addressed cheaply, rather than at delivery when they cannot.",
      "The refit is where ownership quality is renewed. It is also where the owner\u2019s representation choice has its highest leverage relative to fee. A competent representative on a EUR 5 million refit, charging EUR 200,000 to EUR 400,000, will save the owner the fee several times over through scope discipline alone.",
    ],
  },

  "07-operations": {
    slug: "07-operations",
    title: "Operations",
    standfirst:
      "The captain hire alone determines whether the yacht is a pleasure or a chronic source of friction. The other five operational decisions compound across the hold.",
    readingTime: "12 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "Operations is the part of yacht ownership that lasts the longest, costs the most over a hold period, and is most often delegated to people the owner has not selected with proper care. The captain hire alone determines whether the yacht is a pleasure or a chronic source of friction. The crew structure, the management company, the insurance arrangement, the regulatory compliance, and the choice of charter or private operation are the five other pillars of an operating decision that compounds across the hold.",
      "This chapter walks through each, with the same editorial frame as the rest of The First Owner’s Reference: the structural points are presented at face value, drawn from the published practitioner record rather than the trade press summary of it.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The captain hire" },
      "The captain is the highest-leverage hire an owner makes. A good captain runs a quiet, profitable yacht with low crew turnover, predictable maintenance costs, and few unpleasant surprises. A poor captain runs a yacht that is always one minor fault away from a major repair, with crew who leave within a season and an operating budget that rises every year for reasons that are never quite explained.",
      "The pay differential between a good captain and a competent average one is small. The operational differential is large. YPI Crew's 2026 salary guide places captain pay on a 50 to 60 metre yacht at EUR 10,000 to 16,000 per month. Quay Crew records average pay rising from around EUR 6,000 per month on a 20 to 24 metre yacht to over EUR 25,000 on a 100 to 119 metre vessel. Quay Crew also notes the 70 to 79m bracket saw a 7 percent year-on-year increase against the 2023 survey, and 63 percent of captains are now on time-for-time rotation.",
      "The framework for captain selection that practitioners across the industry consistently endorse: hire the candidate who pushes back hardest. Captains who agree easily to the owner's first proposed itinerary, intended use pattern, or maintenance schedule are pleasant in the interview and expensive in the second year. The captain who asks \"what is the actual use pattern, who is the family, what is your tolerance for transit days, what is your budget for refit reserves\" is the captain to hire. The reflexive accommodation in interview is the warning sign.",
      "The independence question applies to the captain hire. A captain who comes recommended by the broker has a relationship with the broker. The broker will benefit if the captain calls them with charter requests or with future yacht acquisition referrals. The owner may or may not benefit from the same relationship. A captain hired through a recruitment agency engaged by the owner's independent adviser is structurally cleaner.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "Captains who agree easily are pleasant to work with and expensive to live with.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "Crew structure by size" },
      "A 40 to 50 metre yacht typically operates with 8 to 12 crew. Captain. Chief Officer. Bosun and one to two deckhands. Chief Engineer. Second Engineer (above 50m). Chief Stew. Two to four interior crew. Chef. Sometimes a sole crew, sometimes a pastry chef on larger yachts.",
      "Above 50 metres the structure expands to 12 to 18 crew. Above 60 metres, 18 to 25. Above 80 metres, 25 to 35 crew. The numbers scale roughly linearly with size to 70 metres and then increase faster as the operational complexity grows.",
      "The crew is the largest single line in the operating budget, 30 to 40 percent of total cost. Crew salary inflation post-pandemic was significant; the bracket between 2021 and 2023 saw double-digit annual increases at junior levels. By 2024 to 2025 the curve has flattened at junior level and continues to rise at senior level. The captain and chief engineer pay growth continues to outpace inflation. Junior crew pay has plateaued.",
      "The operational implication: crew are not a fixed cost. They are a variable cost that the owner manages through retention, reputation, and culture. A yacht that is known to be a good operation, with a captain crew respect, has lower turnover and lower recruitment cost than a yacht with a difficult atmosphere. Turnover compounds. The owner who manages the captain manages the crew. The captain who manages the crew manages the cost.",
      { type: "h2", text: "ISM, MLC, and flag state compliance" },
      "Yachts above 500 gross tonnes operate under the International Safety Management Code, which mandates a documented Safety Management System and regular audit. Yachts engaged in commercial operation (charter) operate under the Maritime Labour Convention, which governs crew working conditions, contracts, hours, and welfare. Both frameworks are binding and audited.",
      "Compliance is delegated to a yacht management company in most cases. Recognised firms include Hill Robinson, Burgess (yacht management arm), Y.CO, Doehle Yachts, Moran, Edmiston (management arm), Camper & Nicholsons (management), and Fraser (management). The management company maintains the SMS, files the regulatory paperwork, runs the audit cycle, and supports the captain on flag state interactions.",
      "Flag state choice (covered in chapter 4) determines which regulator audits, which regulator's manning rules apply, and which jurisdiction's labour law governs crew contracts. Cayman, Marshall Islands, Malta, and the Red Ensign jurisdictions dominate the over-30m segment.",
      "The compliance cost on a 40 metre yacht for ISM, MLC, flag administration, class society fees, and the management company's compliance services typically runs EUR 80,000 to 200,000 per year. This is recurring cost that does not appear in broker-quoted operating budgets.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The insurance market, brokers and underwriting" },
      "Yacht insurance is the most consequential operational decision an owner makes outside the captain hire. It also tends to be the decision taken with the least attention. The hull policy alone covers an asset typically worth between EUR 10 million and EUR 200 million. The broker chosen and the underwriting structure secured behind that broker determine, at claim time, whether the buyer is whole or not.",
      "The hardened market that opened in 2022, with AIG citing 50 to 70 percent rate increases in the London market across 2022 to 2023, reflected sustained Lloyd\u2019s marine underwriting losses across the mid-2010s. The Lloyd\u2019s yacht line ran at loss ratios above 100 percent for several consecutive years (in 2015, approximately GBP 150 million in premium against GBP 210 million in claims, a 140 percent loss ratio), and yacht is widely identified as the worst-performing segment in the Lloyd\u2019s marine portfolio: only around 5 percent of yacht premium written returned a profit between 2011 and 2017. By H1 2024 hull and machinery rates had stabilised. By Q4 2025, Gallagher Specialty reports softening 4 to 7.5 percent for fleets with good loss records. The typical hull rate for a well-maintained 40 to 50 metre yacht: 0.7 to 1.5 percent of insured value annually. Hurricane-exposed regions and smaller yachts pay 2 to 5 percent.",
      "The Bayesian sinking in August 2024, with USD 150 million insured loss, prompted speculation of a fresh hardening cycle. Pantaenius\u2019s Michelle van der Merwe, on the record: \u201cI think everyone thought it was going to have more of an impact than it did.\u201d The market response was selective tightening on crew qualifications and stability management, not blanket rate rises.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The brokers, by relevance to the over-30m segment" },
      "Howden and Pantaenius are the two largest yacht insurance brokers in the over-30m segment globally. The remaining substantial players are AON Marine, Gallagher Specialty, and Marsh.",
      "Howden Group has consolidated significant yacht-specialist capacity over the past decade through a series of acquisitions, building a London-based yacht practice with strong access to Lloyd\u2019s syndicates and the European specialty markets. The firm operates across hull, P&I, war risk, builder\u2019s risk, and charter cover. Strengths include scale, underwriting access, and structuring capability for complex programmes (multiple hulls, charter operations, owner-side aviation). The trade-off is that Howden\u2019s structure favours owners with sophisticated programmes; smaller, single-hull buyers can find the relationship less personal than a specialist alternative.",
      "Pantaenius, founded in Hamburg in 1899, is the reference broker for European yacht insurance and one of the largest yacht-specialist brokers globally. The firm carries deep service capability, strong loss-management track record, and pre-existing relationships across European underwriters, the German marine market, and Lloyd\u2019s. Strengths include responsive claim handling, a yacht-only frame (no commercial-shipping cross-pressures), and disciplined coverage drafting. The trade-off is that the firm\u2019s relationships are weighted toward European underwriters; for owners with a heavy US East Coast use pattern, alternative brokers can sometimes access tighter US rates.",
      "AON Marine offers yacht insurance as part of a broader marine and corporate insurance practice. Strengths are integration with broader risk programmes (where the principal\u2019s family office insurance, aviation cover, and other lines are also placed with AON), global reach, and capital. The trade-off is that yacht specialism is one practice within a multi-line firm; service depth on yacht-specific matters varies by team.",
      "Gallagher Specialty (Arthur J. Gallagher & Co.) operates a strong yacht practice particularly active on the US East Coast. Strengths include US fleet coverage, hurricane region underwriting, and access to US syndicate markets. The trade-off is that for European-domiciled owners or yachts cruising primarily in the Mediterranean, the firm\u2019s European depth is thinner than Pantaenius or Howden.",
      "Marsh, the largest broker by revenue globally, places yacht business through its specialty marine teams. Strengths include capital, global reach, and capability for the largest hulls (above 100 m) where bespoke structuring is required. The trade-off is that yacht-specialist service depth varies; many smaller owners find the firm less responsive than a yacht-only broker on routine matters.",
      "The smaller specialist brokers (Norton & Co, J&H Marsh, AXA Marine, YachtSure, Northstar) carry the rest of the segment. Selection at this level is mostly relationship-based; the underwriting markets accessed are similar to the larger brokers.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The underwriting that sits behind the broker" },
      "The broker accesses the underwriters; the underwriting is what pays at claim time. The two are easy to conflate and rarely should be. Three points matter most.",
      "First, the hull and machinery policy should be written on agreed value, not actual cash value. Agreed value means the insurer and the buyer agree, in advance, on the figure that will be paid in a total loss. Actual cash value means the insurer pays the depreciated market value at the time of loss, which is typically materially less. The premium difference is small; the claim difference can be tens of millions on a large hull.",
      "Second, the agreed value should reflect rebuild cost, not market value. A 50m yacht with an EUR 18 million market value may have a EUR 28 million rebuild cost at a comparable yard. Insuring at market value leaves the owner short on rebuild after a constructive total loss. Howden\u2019s and Pantaenius\u2019s underwriting templates support agreed-value rebuild-basis structures; the buyer needs to ask for them and to verify the figure with a current yard quote.",
      "Third, the policy structure should be reviewed annually for coverage drift. Itinerary changes (US East Coast addition, charter operation introduction, a new cruising area) trigger different coverage requirements. The broker who reviews the programme proactively at renewal is meaningfully different from the broker who simply re-quotes the prior year\u2019s policy.",
      "Lloyd\u2019s of London syndicates underwrite the majority of large-yacht hull capacity. Active syndicates include CNA Hardy, Beazley, Brit, AIG, Liberty Specialty, Tokio Marine HCC, and MS Amlin. The broker\u2019s skill is in placing the risk across the right lead and follow capacity to secure the best terms. AXA, Allianz, Generali, and Helvetia also underwrite directly on European-domiciled programmes.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The five lines of cover, on a typical large yacht" },
      "An over-30m programme will typically carry five distinct lines of insurance, each separately underwritten and renewed.",
      "Hull and machinery, covering loss or damage to the yacht itself. Premium 0.7 to 1.5 percent of insured value annually for well-maintained 40 to 50 m hulls; 2 to 5 percent for smaller yachts and hurricane-exposed regions.",
      "P&I (protection and indemnity), covering crew injury, environmental damage, third-party liability, and charter guest claims. Shipowners\u2019 Club and Steamship Mutual dominate the over-30m segment. Cover is routinely written to EUR 500 million third-party limit.",
      "War risk, purchased per voyage rather than annually. Pre-October 2023 Red Sea war risk was 0.05 percent of hull value per voyage. By early 2024, 1 percent. At peaks, 2 percent. Black Sea (Russian ports) currently 0.65 to 0.80 percent. Ukrainian deep-water ports 0.45 to 0.55 percent.",
      "Builder\u2019s risk, during refit and new build. Typically taken out by the yard with the owner\u2019s interest noted. The buyer should verify named-insured status, deductible, and that the policy covers transit between subcontractor sites.",
      "Charter operation cover, where applicable. Charter activities require uplift on hull and P&I to reflect the elevated risk profile. The charter management company will normally co-ordinate this; the owner\u2019s broker should confirm the structure.",
      "An owner who economises on the broker selection or on underwriting attention is making a high-leverage decision badly. The fee differential between a yacht-specialist broker (Howden or Pantaenius) and a generalist broker is small. The claim differential, when it matters, can run into eight figures.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Charter operation" },
      "The decision to operate a yacht commercially through charter is a separate decision from the ownership decision and is too often bundled into broker pitches as if the two were one.",
      "Charter operation requires commercial registration (typically through the French Commercial Exemption, Maltese commercial registration, or equivalent), MLC compliance, a charter management company, and a charter brokerage relationship. The economics, as covered in chapter 1, are unfavourable for the median operation. Most charter yachts subsidise rather than recover ownership cost.",
      "A 48m motor yacht at EUR 250,000 to 310,000 per week, 7 charter weeks: EUR 1,592,000 income against EUR 1,575,000 cost, break-even (BOAT International). A 47m sail at 9 weeks: EUR 444,000 loss. An 85m motor at 8 weeks: EUR 430,000 loss. The owner-optimised 60m at 12 weeks generates up to EUR 2 million net positive, and depends on disciplined operation, premium rates, and willingness to give up the prime weeks of the season.",
      "For a first-time owner, charter is normally a poor decision in the first three years. The yacht has not yet established a charter reputation. The crew are still settling. The owner has not yet developed the discipline to release the prime weeks. The default should be private operation for the first three years, with a deliberate decision in year four whether to introduce charter, based on actual usage patterns and a clear-eyed projection of charter economics.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The five operational decisions of year one" },
      "In rough order of leverage:",
      "1. Captain hire. Commit to interviewing five candidates minimum, all sourced through routes outside the broker's relationship. The captain you hire determines the next decade.",
      "2. Yacht management company. Engage one independent of the broker's recommendation. The management company is the long-running operational partner. The choice should reflect that, not the broker's referral fee economics.",
      "3. Insurance broker selection. Pantaenius, AON, or Gallagher. All three quote competitively for the over-30m segment. Do not default to whichever broker the seller used.",
      "4. Charter or private decision. Default to private for years one to three. The decision to charter is one to make deliberately, with the data of actual private use to inform it.",
      "5. Refit reserve and capex planning. Build a refit reserve from year one. The five-year survey is real; the ten-year refit is real. An owner who has not been building a reserve discovers in year four that they are underwater on cash flow.",
      "These five decisions, taken with the right advisers and the right discipline, define operations. The captain runs the yacht; the management company runs the compliance; the insurance broker runs the risk; the charter decision runs the commercial strategy; the refit reserve runs the capital plan. The owner runs the team.",
    ],
  },

  "08-motor-versus-sail": {
    slug: "08-motor-versus-sail",
    title: "Motor versus sail",
    standfirst:
      "The chapter most first-time buyers skim. Sailing yacht and motor yacht are not two flavours of the same product; they are different operating regimes with different cost shapes, different carbon profiles, and different markets behind them.",
    readingTime: "13 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "There is a well-rehearsed conversation in which the choice between a sailing yacht and a motor yacht is presented as a question of taste. Quiet anchorages against speed. The thrill of canvas against the convenience of fly bridges. The framing is convenient for those selling either kind of hull, because both kinds of hull deliver a transaction. It is not the most useful frame for a buyer trying to plan a decade of ownership.",
      "The honest comparison runs across operating cost, carbon profile, intended cruising pattern, residual value, and a small but growing third path of hybrid and electric drive. This chapter walks through each, and finishes on the three threshold tests that tend to decide the matter for any specific buyer.",
      "The market is asymmetric to start with. BOAT International\u2019s 2026 Global Order Book records sailing yachts at roughly 12 percent of units on order against 88 percent motor. The Camper & Nicholsons and SuperYacht Times brokerage data places sailing yachts at around 18 percent of the active over-30 m fleet. The numbers are pulled toward motor by the Italian volume yards and the strong American 30 to 50 m motor market. The serious sailing yacht builders, Royal Huisman, Vitters, Baltic Yachts, Perini Navi, Wally, sit in a smaller category by units and a larger one by hold value.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Operating cost, line by line" },
      "A 50 metre sailing yacht runs meaningfully less than a 50 metre motor yacht of comparable build quality. The differential rarely surfaces in broker conversations because brokers handle the two segments separately and there is no commercial reason to walk a buyer between them. The practitioner ranges, from a Foreland archive of managed projects:",
      "Fuel. A 50 m motor yacht running 400 hours a year burns EUR 200,000 to 350,000 in diesel. A 50 m sailing yacht of comparable size, operated primarily under sail, burns EUR 60,000 to 120,000. Most of the differential is not the silent night at anchor; it is the long passage made without engines.",
      "Crew. A 50 m sailing yacht typically operates with 9 to 12 crew against 12 to 16 on a motor yacht of comparable size. Sail-handling specialism on the deck team adds modest cost; the engine room and interior tend to run lighter. Quay Crew\u2019s 2025/26 report records sailing yacht captain pay slightly below motor at equivalent length, although the experienced sailing yacht captain market is thinner and competition for the best of them is real.",
      "Maintenance. Sailing yachts of quality build carry rigging and sail wardrobe maintenance that motor yachts do not. A full sail wardrobe replacement at 7 to 10 year intervals runs EUR 400,000 to 1.2 million depending on size. Standing rigging replacement at the 10 to 15 year mark runs EUR 250,000 to 700,000. Set against that, sailing yachts carry less main-engine wear, smaller stabiliser systems on many designs, and simpler hydraulic and HVAC loads. Net annual maintenance is broadly comparable; the cost shape differs.",
      "Berths. Berth pricing is by length overall rather than by category, so a sailing yacht and a motor yacht of the same length pay roughly the same in the Mediterranean and Caribbean. A handful of marinas (Antibes, Saint Tropez, Newport, Saint Maarten) hold preferred slots for sailing yachts of significance during regatta windows; that is opportunity rather than discount.",
      "Total operating cost. A 50 m sailing yacht at moderate use typically runs 70 to 85 percent of the equivalent motor yacht\u2019s annual cost. The differential narrows in the 24 to 40 metre band, where motor yachts are smaller and proportionally more efficient, and widens above 60 metres, where motor fuel and crew cost grow disproportionately.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The carbon profile, with the relevant nuance" },
      "Three regulatory and market shifts have changed the carbon conversation since 2020.",
      "The EU Emissions Trading System Maritime extension is the most consequential. In force from 1 January 2024, it covers ships of and above 5,000 gross tonnage calling at EEA ports. Compliance phased in at 40 percent of 2024 emissions in 2025, 70 percent of 2025 emissions in 2026, and 100 percent of 2026 emissions from 2027. Methane and nitrous oxide are added from 2026. Most yachts sit below 5,000 GT (a 60 m motor yacht is typically 700 to 1,200 GT), so the financial bite of EU ETS lands on the very large motor yachts above the threshold. Industry estimates place the cost on a 90 metre motor yacht above 5,000 GT at EUR 200,000 to 400,000 per year on current carbon prices. Comparable sailing yachts at the same size pay materially less.",
      "The methane line in EU ETS is worth a clarifying sentence because it is widely misunderstood. The methane addition from 2026 matters most for vessels burning LNG, where methane slip is significant; for the diesel-fuelled main engines and the diesel hotel-load generators that run on most yachts, methane emissions are negligible and the practical taxation effect is on CO2. The methane line in the regulation is not a meaningful new tax on yacht hotel load. Owners considering LNG-fuelled new builds should treat the methane provision as material; owners on diesel can read it as a non-event.",
      "The IMO 2023 Strategy on Reduction of GHG Emissions from Ships, adopted at MEPC 80 in July 2023, sets a 20 percent reduction (striving for 30 percent) in well-to-wake greenhouse gas emissions by 2030, 70 percent (striving for 80 percent) by 2040, and net zero by or around 2050, against 2008 levels. Resolution MEPC.377(80) is the formal instrument. The strategy is shaping the commercial shipping fuel transition that, in turn, reaches yachting through fuel availability and fuel cost.",
      "The most consequential near-term answer in the yacht segment is hydrotreated vegetable oil. HVO is a paraffinic diesel produced from waste fats and vegetable oils. It is a true drop-in replacement for marine gas oil: existing engines, fuel systems, and tanks accept it without modification. Lifecycle CO2 emissions are 85 to 90 percent below fossil diesel on well-to-wheel analysis. Cetane number is above 70, which gives cleaner combustion and a small power benefit. Bunker availability is uneven (Mediterranean coverage is strongest, Caribbean and US East Coast weaker, with a mixed picture elsewhere) and per-tonne pricing typically sits around 30 to 50 percent above mineral diesel. Feadship\u2019s 84 metre Obsidian, launched in 2023, was the first delivery yacht to run on HVO; uptake among other quality builders has accelerated since. For an owner who wants a defensible carbon position without rebuilding the engine room, HVO is the easiest move available, and the natural fuel for any yacht where bunkering allows.",
      "Methanol and hydrogen-fuel-cell drives are also moving from concept to delivery, although both require significant new-build engineering. Methanol-ready arrangements are appearing in the larger Northern European order books; hydrogen storage and fuel-cell systems are at concept and pilot stage. For most readers, HVO and hybrid drive (below) are the practical near-term options.",
      "The owner-side conversation has changed too. Capgemini\u2019s 2024 World Wealth Report puts sustainability among the top three concerns for next-generation HNWIs, ahead of returns in some segments. A yacht is conspicuous in a way that a family office\u2019s liquid portfolio is not, and a growing number of principals want the carbon question answered in advance, on terms they have chosen. A serious 50 m sailing yacht programme runs 60 to 70 percent below the comparable motor programme on annual carbon footprint, on Royal Huisman\u2019s published sustainability data and aggregated practitioner numbers. The gap is large and structurally durable.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "Sailing yachts are not zero-carbon. They are structurally cleaner than motor yachts by a margin that family offices have begun to model rather than apologise for.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "Hybrid and electric drive, the third path" },
      "Hybrid propulsion has moved from concept to delivery in the past five years and changes the framing of the motor versus sailing yacht decision in ways the trade press has not fully caught up with. Two builders are the published reference points.",
      "Heesen Yachts\u2019 hybrid programme is the deepest commercial deployment of parallel diesel-electric propulsion in the production-yacht segment. The 50 metre FDHF aluminium series (delivered hulls include Home, Amare II, and Project Orion in early 2025) pairs two main diesels, two diesel generators, and two electric motors that can be operated separately or in any combination. Owners use the electric mode for harbour transits, anchor approaches, and short coastal hops, with the diesels held back for passage work. Owners report meaningful annual fuel reductions; the operational character is closer to a sailing yacht\u2019s silence at anchor than to conventional motor.",
      "Royal Huisman has taken the deeper-engineering route. Aquarius II, a 65 metre sailing yacht, integrates a 580 kWh battery bank capable of running the entire hotel load silently for around 11 hours, with hydro-generators trickle-charging the bank under sail. The shipyard\u2019s AERA concept, developed with Rondal, Artemis Technologies, and Cor D. Rover Design, layers wind-assisted propulsion, hydro-generation, and a hydrogen fuel cell with three pressurised hydrogen bottles for up to 72 hours of zero-emission operation. AERA remains a concept; the technologies behind it are in delivered hulls.",
      "For the buyer thinking about the next ten years, hybrid and electric capability is now a question to ask of any new build at every yard, sailing yacht or motor yacht. Bering Yachts, Wider, Sanlorenzo (with the SX series), Lurssen, Feadship, and Oceanco all have hybrid hulls in build or delivered. The 5,000 GT threshold problem aside, a hybrid motor yacht with strong battery hotel-load capability narrows the carbon gap to a sailing yacht meaningfully. The decision is no longer two-way; it is three-way, with hybrid sitting between.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Racing pedigree and value retention" },
      "Racing is the part of the sailing yacht world the trade press covers least carefully and the part that does most to support residual values at the top of the segment. Three circuits matter.",
      "The J Class circuit. Nine J Class hulls are currently active in the fleet: three surviving originals (Velsheda, Shamrock, Endeavour) refitted for cruising and racing, and six modern builds since 2003 (Ranger, Rainbow, Hanuman, Lionheart, Topaz, Svea). They race at Newport, the Saint Barths Bucket, the Maxi Yacht Rolex Cup, and the J Class World Championship. A further hull is reported in build at Brodotrogir in Croatia. The hulls hold value materially better than comparable cruising sailing yachts, on the strength of provenance, regatta access, and the closed-class nature of the racing. A J Class hull is, in practice, a hold-forever asset for the families who own them.",
      "The Maxi and Wally circuit. The Maxi Yacht Rolex Cup at Porto Cervo, the Voiles de Saint Tropez, the Loro Piana Superyacht Regatta, and the Antigua Bermuda Race form the Mediterranean and transatlantic Maxi season. Wally hulls (Wally B, Wallygator series, the Wally 80 to 130 range) trade actively in the brokerage market with strong residuals at the top of the range.",
      "The Royal Ocean Racing Club calendar. The Fastnet, the RORC Caribbean 600, the Middle Sea Race, the Transatlantic Race. These are the offshore-capable yachts (typically 18 to 30 metres) for which the racing pedigree adds genuine resale value. A yacht with podium finishes on the RORC calendar carries a premium of 10 to 25 percent over a comparable cruising hull, on broker-aggregated data.",
      "Two 2025 reference points illustrate the segment\u2019s health. Edmiston and Nautor Swan announced an alloy sailing yacht range at the 2025 Palm Beach International Boat Show, designed by Malcolm McKeon Yacht Design, with Edmiston\u2019s Newport, Rhode Island office serving as the operational hub. McKeon\u2019s studio is also responsible for the 83 metre Feadship Project Solent, on which Cecil Wright is acting as owner\u2019s representative for delivery in summer 2027. Separately, Tom Cruise commissioned a Swan 108 in February 2025: a 33 metre carbon-fibre racing-capable sailing yacht under construction at Nautor Swan, Jakobstad, with estimated total cost above USD 30 million. The First Owner’s Reference does not write on celebrity ownership for its own sake. The relevant signal is that committed capital and significant design houses are building modern sailing yachts at the top end of the market in numbers the order book does not yet show.",
      "Behind those reference points sits a broader brokerage pattern. Sailing yachts in the 25 to 45 metre band moved at median days on market of approximately 220 in 2025, against 277 for comparable motor yachts on Denison\u2019s series. The disciplined hulls move. The segment is healthier than the headline unit-share suggests.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Bang for buck, on a 35 metre" },
      "For a buyer in the 24 to 40 metre band, a sailing yacht typically delivers more cruising days per pound or euro than a motor yacht of comparable build quality. The case is straightforward.",
      "A new build 35 metre sailing yacht from a quality builder (Pendennis, Vitters, Baltic) runs EUR 12 to 22 million depending on specification. A new build 35 metre motor yacht of comparable build quality runs EUR 18 to 30 million. The capital differential is 20 to 35 percent in favour of the sailing yacht. Annual operating cost runs 70 to 85 percent of the motor figure on equivalent length and use. The constraint on cruising days is rarely the hull; it is the owner\u2019s availability. But the running cost differential allows a sailing yacht to be operated more weeks per year on the same opex envelope. A EUR 1.5 million annual operating budget tends to deliver 16 to 20 weeks of family use on a 35 metre sailing yacht, against 12 to 14 weeks on the equivalent motor yacht.",
      "Depreciation. Quality sailing yachts hold value materially better than comparable motor yachts in the 30 to 50 metre band, on broker-aggregated data. The top of the sailing-yacht builder set (Royal Huisman, Vitters, Baltic, Perini Navi) shows single-digit annual depreciation after year five, against 5 to 8 percent for top motor builders. Across a seven-year hold a 35 metre sailing yacht programme typically runs 25 to 40 percent below the equivalent motor programme on total cost (capex plus opex minus residual). Brokers do not present this comparison because the two segments are sold by different desks. The arithmetic is, nonetheless, what it is.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Where the case for sail does not hold" },
      "There are owners for whom a sailing yacht is the wrong answer, and the cases are worth naming.",
      "Sailing yachts ask more from the operation. Sail-handling expertise on the deck team, weather routing discipline, and itineraries that bend to the wind. An owner who needs to cross the Atlantic on a fixed schedule with no flexibility on the weather window is not a sailing-yacht owner. An owner comfortable with a 36 to 60 hour weather window for a transatlantic is.",
      "Sailing yachts are heavier on the body and on time. A motor yacht delivers a steady ride at displacement speed. A sailing yacht heels, accelerates, decelerates, and asks more of the people aboard. Older owners, owners with mobility constraints, and owners who use the yacht primarily for entertaining rather than cruising are often better served by a motor yacht (or a hybrid one).",
      "The supply side is thinner. There are fewer high-quality sailing yacht builders, fewer slot opportunities, and a smaller pool of comparable hulls in the brokerage market. A buyer who wants a 35 metre sailing yacht in 2027 has a shorter list of credible options than a buyer looking for a 35 metre motor yacht. The market is healthy; it is small.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Three threshold tests" },
      "Three questions tend to decide it for any specific buyer.",
      "First, what does the cruising calendar look like? An owner whose programme depends on fixed-date passages with no weather contingency is on the motor or hybrid side. An owner with a season of cruising flexibility is on the sailing-yacht side, or has a real choice across all three.",
      "Second, how exposed is the buyer to the carbon question? A principal whose family office, foundation, or public profile pulls at the carbon line will sit closer to the sailing yacht or hybrid side. A principal for whom carbon is not a board-level conversation will weight the cruising-calendar question more heavily.",
      "Third, what is the seven-year arithmetic? Run capex, opex, depreciation, and residual against the buyer\u2019s actual use case before defaulting either way. Most first-time buyers default to motor without doing the comparison; some of them are right to, others are not.",
      "The chapter does not arbitrate between motor and sail. It asks the comparison to be run on variables that move, with hybrid drive considered a third option rather than a footnote, and the regulatory weather watched rather than ignored.",
    ],
  },

  "09-decision-framework": {
    slug: "09-decision-framework",
    title: "The decision framework",
    standfirst:
      "Building the team that protects you, in the order that matters. The independence test, applied transparently to every adviser including us.",
    readingTime: "8 min read",
    paragraphs: [
      "The UBS Global Family Office Report 2025 is the most comprehensive survey of how the world's largest private wealth holders allocate capital. It runs to 80 pages, covers 317 family offices, and analyses an average AUM per office of USD 1.1 billion against an average family net worth of USD 2.7 billion. Across that document, yachts do not appear. Not in any year. Not in any region. Not in any sub-allocation. Not in real estate, not in alternatives, not in art and antiques. The asset that sits in the harbour outside the principal's office is not in the books that the family office prepares for the principal.",
      "This is not an oversight. It is the structural reality of how superyachts are bought.",
      "This chapter is the closing argument of The First Owner’s Reference. It tells the reader how to build the team that protects them, in what order to make the appointments, how to test any adviser they are considering (including us), and why the moment they are reading this is the moment that matters.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The largest wealth transfer in history" },
      "The Capgemini World Wealth Report 2025, the 29th edition of the standard reference, finds that USD 83.5 trillion of wealth will be inherited by Generation X, millennials, and Generation Z by 2048. Within that transfer, women receive a significant share by 2035. And, crucially, 81 percent of next-generation HNWIs intend to switch from their parents' wealth management firm within one to two years of inheritance.",
      "The reader of The First Owner’s Reference is therefore likely to be one of two profiles. The first is a newly liquidated principal, recently exited from a business, sitting on USD 20 to USD 500 million, considering a first yacht acquisition. The second is an heir whose first action upon inheritance is to evaluate the advisers their parents used and replace those who are not aligned. Both profiles share an essential characteristic: they are entering an asset class without the experience to navigate it, and they are doing so at a moment when the existing advisers around them are structurally conflicted.",
      "The Knight Frank Family Office Survey 2026, drawn from interviews with more than 40 family offices in London, New York, Dubai, Singapore, and Hong Kong, identifies the gap. The survey explicitly names superyachts in the portfolio architecture for the first time:",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "Digital aggregation, enabling live, consolidated tracking of complex portfolios, from liquid assets to superyachts and real estate.",
        attribution: "Knight Frank Family Office Survey 2026",
      },
      "Family offices are now actively working to integrate yachts into the portfolio frame. The tooling and the institutional competence for it are still being established. The structural matter is not technology. It is that the industry that sells these assets has limited incentive to make their financial behaviour transparent to a family office applying full fiduciary scrutiny.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The independence test" },
      "Several firms describe themselves as independent. The word does meaningful work in some cases and is decorative in others. The independence test has six elements. It applies to any adviser the reader is considering, including the publisher of The First Owner’s Reference. The publisher's own answers are set out on the colophon.",
      "1. Does the firm earn anything contingent on a transaction closing? If yes, they are not independent of the deal. Brokers, charter brokers, management companies that receive yard referral fees, design firms that take commission on builder selection, all fail this test. They may still provide value. They are not independent of the transaction's closing.",
      "2. Does the firm hold any equity, employment, or referral relationship with any yard, broker, supplier, management company, or charter operation? If yes, they are not independent of those counterparties. A management company that is owned by a brokerage is not independent of that brokerage's broker recommendations. A design firm that has a continuing relationship with three yards is not independent in counselling on yard selection.",
      "3. Does the firm publish a complete list of every counterparty they have worked with in the past three years, with the nature of the relationship? If no, the reader cannot test claims one and two. The independence claim becomes assertion rather than evidence.",
      "4. Are the firm's fees transparent and quoted in writing in advance? If no, the structure can hide commissions. A firm that charges hourly without a cap, or on a percentage basis without a clear scope, has the latitude to extract value the buyer cannot price.",
      "5. Does the firm hold professional indemnity insurance at a level appropriate to the transaction? If no, the firm cannot afford to be wrong on the buyer's behalf. A USD 50 million build with an adviser carrying GBP 1 million of professional indemnity is not insured against the actual scale of the project.",
      "6. Are the firm's principals named, traceable, and accountable? If no, none of the above can be verified. Anonymous firms, firms registered in jurisdictions that do not require beneficial ownership disclosure, firms whose principals do not appear in public communications, fail the most basic accountability test.",
      "These six questions apply to anyone proposing to advise on the acquisition. They also serve as the rough framework for due diligence on a wealth manager, a lawyer, a surveyor, a captain candidate. The principles are not yacht-specific. They are the principles of fiduciary alignment, applied to an industry that has structurally avoided them.",
      { type: "h2", text: "Building the team, in priority order" },
      "The order in which the buyer hires the team determines the quality of every subsequent decision. Most first-time buyers hire in the wrong order. The right order:",
      "1. Independent adviser. Engaged before any broker, any captain, any management company. The independent adviser's role is to scope the acquisition, evaluate brokers, support the negotiation, and build the rest of the team.",
      "2. Yacht lawyer. Specialist shipbuilding and yacht counsel from a recognised firm (Hill Dickinson, Watson Farley & Williams, Ince, Stephenson Harwood, Reed Smith, HFW, Norton Rose Fulbright). Engaged before any contract is reviewed. The independent adviser will introduce candidates without conflict.",
      "3. Surveyor. Engaged on a per-deal basis once a shortlist exists. Independent of the broker. Recognised firms include Wolfson Marine, Ward & McKenzie, Patton Marine, Winterbothams. The surveyor's report is paid for by the buyer.",
      "4. Captain candidate (or build captain on new build). Hired through routes independent of the broker. Interviewed at length. The captain should be involved in survey, sea trial, and acceptance decisions.",
      "5. Yacht management company. Engaged once the acquisition decision is taken. Independent of the broker. The management company is the long-running operational partner.",
      "6. Insurance broker. Engaged once flag state and operating profile are determined. Pantaenius, AON, Gallagher all quote competitively.",
      "The cost of the entire team, on a USD 30 to 50 million acquisition, runs USD 200,000 to 600,000 across the first year, depending on scope and project complexity. On a transaction of that size, this is a rounding error. Owners who economise on it are saving tenths of percentage points to lose multiples of percentage points in the asset itself.",
      {
        type: "blockquote",
        text: "The right order is independent adviser, then lawyer, then surveyor, then captain. Most first-time buyers do this in reverse.",
      },
      { type: "h2", text: "The ten questions" },
      "A one-page checklist the reader can apply before signing anything.",
      "1. Who introduced the yacht (or yard) to me, and who pays them?",
      "2. Who recommended the lawyer, and who pays them?",
      "3. Who recommended the surveyor, and who pays them?",
      "4. Who recommended the management company, and who pays them?",
      "5. Has any party offered to provide their services \"at no cost,\" and if so, who is paying them?",
      "6. Has every party I am working with disclosed their commercial relationships in writing, including referral fees, retrocessions, and equity holdings in counterparties?",
      "7. Is my legal counsel independent of the broker, the yard, and the management company, and is their fee paid by me directly?",
      "8. Is my surveyor independent of the seller and of the broker, and is their fee paid by me directly?",
      "9. If I am building, is my owner's representative paid solely by me, with no contingent fee, no yard commission, and no referral relationship?",
      "10. If I asked any of these parties to walk away from a deal that would not benefit me, would they?",
      "A buyer who can answer all ten questions clearly, with documentary evidence, is exceptionally well-protected. The buyer who cannot is, by industry default, operating in the structure described across the earlier chapters. That is information rather than judgment.",
      { type: "h2", text: "The closing argument" },
      "The First Owner’s Reference exists because trade press is structurally less able to publish what is set out across these chapters. Trade press is not a moral failing of the people who work in it. It is a structural fact about how that industry funds itself. The publisher of The First Owner’s Reference is funded by independent consultancy work rather than by advertising. That structural difference is the entire publication. The publisher\u2019s full disclosure, including its own answers to the six-element independence test, is set out on the colophon.",
      "For a reader considering a first yacht acquisition, whether as a newly liquidated principal or as an heir for whom the family yacht has become a new responsibility, the next three months are the most consequential of ownership. The decisions made in that window, about the team built, set the trajectory of the next ten years.",
      "The single most important of those decisions is to engage an adviser who is structurally aligned with the buyer, before engaging anyone who is structurally aligned with someone else. That is the argument. The rest is detail.",
      "There are several such advisers. The publisher of The First Owner’s Reference is one of them. The independence test, applied to all of them, is how the right one is chosen.",
    ],
  },
};

export function getLeadEssay(slug: string): LeadEssay | undefined {
  return leadEssays[slug];
}
